<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 92 / Commodities and Agriculture (Week in the Markets): Coffee
gets back into bullish mood
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD MOONEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORLD coffee market's bullish sentiment was re-emphasised this week as
the March arabica futures position in New York moved above the
psychologically-important 70 cents-a-lb mark and London's robusta futures
established fresh nine-month highs.
These rises justified the view expressed by most traders that last week's
fall, which took the January delivery price in London down Dollars 31 to
Dollars 910 a tonne, was a 'technical correction' following the sustained
upsurge that had lifted the January price by Dollars 120 since the beginning
of October.
The upward trend was resumed in New York on Monday, after FO Licht, the
German statistics agency, predicted that world coffee production would fall
by 8.67m bags (60 kg each) to 93.32m bags in the 1992-93 season. It was
quickly followed up in London, fuelled by covering purchases by operators
who had sold the market short last week.
The prospect of a small Brazilian coffee crop has been the main factor
driving the market higher; ED &amp; F. Man, the London trade house, recently
forecast that the country's 1992-93 crop would total 19.15m bags - at the
low end of recent predictions. And this gloomy view of the outlook for the
world's biggest coffee supplier was supported this week by news that it
exported only 1.36m bags in October, 810,000 less than in the same month
last year.
The market remained bullish yesterday morning, when London's January futures
position reached Dollars 980 a tonne, but it slipped back to Dollars 959 a
tonne up Dollars 49 on the week and Dollars 283 above the 20-year low
reached in the summer.
Traders thought further gains were possible, although modest producer
selling was likely to appear as prices rose. One sounded a note of caution,
however. 'Probably you've a little bit of resistance from these levels up to
the Dollars 1,000 level,' he told the Reuter news agency, 'and the Dollars
1,000 on January is always going to be a psychological barrier'.
London cocoa prices also touched fresh nine-month highs in mid-week, but the
gains were quickly surrendered, with traders arguing that the market was in
need of 'consolidation' following last week's sharp gains. The March cocoa
futures position ended at Pounds 758 a tonne, up Pounds 6 on the week.
The market impact of the two-week international cocoa agreement negotiations
in Geneva, which finished yesterday, was negligible. Nothing conclusive was
expected to emerge from the producer-consumer talks - and nothing did. There
was progress in narrowing the gaps between the two sides on the price range
to be defended by a new agreement and the amount of stocks to be withdrawn
from the market, but they remained wide. These questions, together with the
knotty problem of financing price support efforts, will be tackled again at
the next negotiating session between February 22 and March 5 next year. That
will be the last chance to agree a replacement pact before the present one,
which operates no price-support arrangements, expires next September.
At the London bullion market the gold price, battered in recent months by
central bank selling and 'panic' hedging sales by producers, came under
further pressure from Middle Eastern sales and slumped to a seven-year low
of Dollars 329.30 a troy ounce at one point. But with analysts arguing that
the market had become heavily oversold, trade and speculative buyers were
quick to come to the rescue and the price closed yesterday at Dollars 336.45
an ounce, up Dollars 2.40 on the week.
Platinum also rallied sharply after a heavy fall in the first half of the
week, but the price was still Dollars 12.85 down on balance at yesterday's
fixing level of Dollars 353.65 an ounce. The recovery from Wednesday's
Dollars 347.25 an ounce was encouraged, dealers said, by a mildly bullish
Interim Review from Johnson Matthey, the world's biggest platinum marketing
group. JM forecast that the metal's price would average Dollars 370 an ounce
in the final quarter of this year and Dollars 385 an ounce in the first
quarter of 1993.
Silver displayed a similar pattern to the other precious metals, ending 10
cents down on the week at 379.5 cents an ounce.
Base metals prices see-sawed at the London Metal Exchange. Early losses were
generally recovered in a mid-week rally but fresh falls yesterday left most
prices lower. The biggest loser was nickel, which ended Dollars 170 down on
the week in the three months position at a five-year low of Dollars 5,497.50
a tonne after another big rise in LME warehouse stocks was announced.
