<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 92 / Letter: Pay clamp on public sector will depress economy in
short term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr KEITH FLETT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, David Goodhart's article on the government's attempt to impose a 1.5
per cent pay ceiling ('Public pay feels the squeeze', November 13) focuses
on the possible longer-term impact of a restriction on public sector pay.
But a pay ceiling, which is likely to have as big, or as little, an impact
in the private as the public sector, also has immediate implications. First,
if what amounts to a wage cut is carried through, this will do little to
reflate the economy. Demand will be depressed further.
Second, if wages are reined in but prices and profits are left where they
are, this will do little to move Britain towards Mr Major's dream of a
classless society. For example, how can a rise of between 7 and 8 per cent
in British Rail and London Transport fares be justified against a maximum
1.5 per cent pay rise?
Since 1979, the government has put forward some very good arguments about
why government intervention in wage settlements does not work. These still
seem to have considerable validity, despite this latest U-turn.
Keith Flett,
38 Mitchley Road,
Tottenham
London N17 9HG
