<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 92 / Insurers challenge proposed regulator
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ASSOCIATION of British Insurers, the main trade body for the insurance
industry, yesterday advised its members to steer clear of the Personal
Investments Authority, a proposed self-regulatory body for financial
services.
It said it wanted to wait until 95 per cent of potential members of the new
body had joined it.
The ABI said yesterday that, if the industry did not give full support to
the new authority on a voluntary basis, 'there is a strong case for
legislation to remove the Securities and Investments Board's powers of
direct regulation'.
That statement further undermines the prospects of the proposed body, which
is intended to include not only life insurers and independent financial
advisers, but also banks and building societies which sell financial
services.
Most UK banks and building societies are members of SIB's own direct
self-regulatory body, known as Sibro, and of Imro, the self-regulatory body
for the financial services industry.
The life insurers and independent financial advisers are members of Lautro
and Fimbra. The association said that SIB's announced intention to treat the
Personal Investments Authority as the 'lead regulator' for firms which were
members of Sibro did not go far enough.
Banks and building societies and several of the larger independent financial
adviser networks have expressed great reluctance to join the new authority
and say that retail regulation should be best accomplished by merging Lautro
and Fimbra.
Meanwhile, the association has spelled out a number of changes it wishes to
see to the charter of the new authority, which is intended to be produced in
final form in January.
