<HEADLINE>
FT  14 NOV 92 / Kmart founder dies aged 85
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Harry Blair Cunningham, former chairman of Kmart, the large US retail
group, and one of the best-known figures in US retailing since the war, has
died, Nikki Tait reports from New York. Mr Cunningham was 85.
Mr Cunningham is widely credited with first introducing discount retailing
to American shoppers on a big scale and effectively creating today's Kmart
store chain in the process.
He became manager of a Kresge store, one of the hundred of outlets built up
by Mr Sebastian Kresge after the first world war. By 1959 he had risen to
become president of the SS Kresge group.
It was three years later, in 1962, that the Kresge company opened its first
Kmart discount store in a Detroit suburb, a retail formula which proved
immensely successful. In an expansion blitz, it exploded to 1,200 outlets by
the mid-1970s. Recognising that discount stores had become the mainstay of
the group, shareholders approved a change in the company's name to Kmart in
1977.
</TEXT>
