<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Jordanian MPs are pardoned by Hussein
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES WHITTINGTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   AMMAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JORDAN's King Hussein yesterday freed two parliamentarians sentenced this
week to 20 years' hard labour for allegedly conspiring to overthrow the
government, as part of a general amnesty for 140 political and criminal
prisoners.
Mr Lieth Shbeilat and Mr Ya'aqub Qarrash, along with two merchants from
Amman, were found guilty by the State Security Court on Tuesday after one of
Jordan's most controversial political trials.
The amnesty also includes several members of Hamas, a militant Islamic
group, imprisoned last year for possession of weapons, along with a number
of Palestinians belonging to the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine held recently on similar charges.
In a public announcement on television King Hussein explained that he was
willing to give the prisoners a chance to go back to the 'path of
righteousness,' saying he believed they had repented the harm they had
caused the country.
Dr Abdul Latif Arabiyat, speaker of the elected lower house of parliament,
welcomed the pardon, saying: 'We are in a transitional stage between the law
of this military court and the King's way. . . this act shows that our
democratic march is very strong. . . the (MPs') slate has been wiped clean.'
Sources close to the king explained that the pardon was a humanitarian
gesture in advance of his 57th birthday on Saturday, rather than a rejection
of the military court proceedings which had aroused some concern in Jordan
both for the manner of its conduct and the verdict against the MPs.
Several hundred demonstrators urged King Hussein to intervene personally
during the trial, and Jordan's monarch told the FT last month that he had
been keeping a 'close eye' on the affair.
The pardon is likely to help calm fears that the government was faltering in
its moves towards broadening democracy and should forestall any potential
backlash against the court's initial sentence.
</TEXT>
