<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / International Company News: Further shake-up at Olivetti
aims to cut costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AP-DJ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OLIVETTI, the loss-making Italian computer group, yesterday announced
another corporate restructuring aimed at cutting costs and streamlining
production, AP-DJ reports from Milan.
Olivetti, controlled by financier Mr Carlo De Benedetti, said it had created
three new central divisions and eight new commercial areas in what it
claimed was the second phase of a previous restructuring announced one year
ago.
'Our group today is the algebraic sum of areas where it earns and grows well
and areas where it continues to lose . . . The objective is to develop to
the maximum the first and intervene drastically in the second in a very
brief time,' Mr De Benedetti said in a statement.
Yesterday's statement reversed a previous restructuring announced last
November, which, in turn, had rolled back another reorganisation in 1989.
The three new divisions are products, systems and professional services.
These will replace Olivetti's present three divisions, called diversified
activities, planning and development; public administration; and operations.
Olivetti's commercial areas will grow to eight from five and will be
geographically rearranged 'with the scope of allowing the company to
concentrate in an articulated way its commercial efforts in function of
different geographic opportunities,' the statement said.
Mr De Benedetti said the restructuring will start to pay off in 1994. '1993
will be a transition year, but in 1992 we will reap the fruit of all this
work in an industry that, although experiencing worldwide the worst years of
its history, is due for extraordinary growth over the next 10 years.'
The chairman made no predictions for Olivetti's full-year results this year.
The group's first-half consolidated net loss widened to L93.4bn (Dollars
68.92m) from  73.7bn in 1991.
</TEXT>
