<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (11): Few northern bubbles to burst -
The North / There is a shortage of good modern or new space in some city
centres
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE north of England has been reaping some rewards from being on the wrong
side of Britain's north-south divide in the 1980s. While the south bubbled,
the north's property markets hardly inflated at all, so there were few
northern bubbles to burst when the south's went pop.
Mr Tom Marshall, chief executive of Lambert Smith Hampton in Manchester,
sums up much of the situation in a vast swathe of England from Crewe and
Grimsby northwards to the Scottish border. 'The property market finds itself
in as hostile an environment as any, but has inflicted fewer wounds on
itself over the past five years than is the case for much of the rest of the
country,' he says.
Much of northern England was ignored by national property developers until
very late in the last upward swing of the economic cycle. This was not
because the north was essentially unattractive, but the pickings were easier
and richer in the south.
The result is that there is no serious over-supply of good property anywhere
in the north. Indeed, there is a shortage of good modern or new space in the
city centres of Manchester, Leeds, Liverpool, Sheffield and Newcastle.
Rental levels have softened on some older, refurbished properties, but are
holding at the top end, although Manchester's will be tested in the next few
months as 45,000 sq ft comes on stream at an asking price of Pounds 22 or
Pounds 23 per sq ft.
Leeds, however, has been steady at Pounds 19 a sq ft, with Pounds 20
projected for next year on new space. As Matthews and Goodman - a surveyor
active in London, Liverpool and Manchester - points out, Manchester's top
rents were about Pounds 15 five years ago, although growth there is not as
impressive as in Leeds, where the 1987 level was Pounds 7.
Not everything is wonderful: concessions and incentives are on offer in
several areas to get people to move in, but it is hard to find signs of real
desperation to let or sell. Developers who had stretched too far into debt
to hold on have already gone. For the rest, an absence of glut has enabled a
longer view to be taken.
If there is a problem, it is at Salford Quays, Manchester's docklands at the
terminus of the ship canal. An expiring enterprise zone brought 1m sq ft of
new office space onto the market in a rush in 1990-91, just as demand began
to falter. About 80 per cent is still unlet, but while this hit Charter
Developments hard, others such as the Manchester Ship Canal Company appear
able to afford to sit it out. Meanwhile, Amec - another big Salford Quays
developer - is getting on with serious industrial property projects in the
adjacent Trafford Park urban development area.
Mr Nicholas Kos, a partner in Bailey Deakin Hamiltons, a Preston firm of
chartered surveyors, says that although the market is sluggish and
speculative development has dried up, specific requirements are being met by
bespoke design and build projects.
He also says there is continuing demand for well-located property. Indeed,
location is proving a crucial factor, involving three elements - the
motorway network, proximity to Manchester Airport and the growth of the
financial and professional services sector in Leeds and Manchester.
The last of these is what is keeping up prime office rentals. In both
cities, the financial and professional firms involved operate within walking
distance of each other and employ tens of thousands of people between them.
Manchester Airport, meanwhile, is now the fastest-growing in Europe and is
firmly established as Britain's northern hub and international gateway. This
is spawning its own mini-market, with several sizeable speculative
developments planned. Top rents in nearby Wilmslow, for example, have been a
step ahead of central Manchester's for several years.
The motorways, however, are probably the northern property market's biggest
asset. Good sites near important junctions offer crucial benefits to foreign
inward investors, national relocators, and anyone in the distribution
business.
Warrington and Wakefield - respectively at the crossover points of the M62
with the M6 and M1-A1 - prove the point, with warehouses by the mile or
prestigious new arrivals such as Pioneer, the Japanese audio systems
manufacturer, and Cover Girl, which Procter &amp; Gamble has relocated to
Wakefield from Bournemouth.
The M1 at Sheffield and Rotherham has proved ideal for the new Meadowhall
shopping complex. After two years' operation, only five of 285 units were
unlet and 43m visitors had produced a pedestrian flow higher than London's
Oxford Street. Second-year traffic was 15 per cent up.
Finally, Crewe Business Park offers one of the best examples of how the
north is now outscoring the south. Sokkia, the Japanese manufacturer of
surveying instruments, was faced with a rent review in Crawley, Sussex, from
Pounds 9.50 a sq ft to Pounds 17.
Crewe and Nantwich Urban Renewal built Sokkia a 12,000 sq ft UK headquarters
for Pounds 900,000. It would have cost three times as much to buy a site in
the south-east - and it would have been an unprepossessing infill between
warehouses. And Crewe's green fields will allow 50 per cent expansion of
present buildings, plus the option to almost double the present one-acre
site when Sokkia wants to grow further.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
