<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (9): Hopes punctured - Northern Ireland
/ Recession arrived this year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE recession in commercial property caught up with Northern Ireland this
year. Falling rents and poor demand from tenants punctured hopes that the
Belfast property market would largely escape the downturn. So far, the
decline is less dramatic than on much of the mainland. Top office rents have
dropped from around Pounds 9.50 to Pounds 7-Pounds 9 per sq ft. The market's
problems are largely focused on second-hand stock, of which there is 592,893
sq ft on the market, compared with 115,000 sq ft of new space.
The market's decline is only partially due to the recession. The Belfast
office market is dominated by the public sector, which accounted for 80 per
cent of take-up over the past 15 months. Back office jobs have been
relocated from the mainland and government departments have been moved into
new premises from Stormont, the old parliament outside the city.
But public sector demand for new office space in Belfast is thought to wane,
particularly with mounting constraints on public spending. Even so, the poor
quality of much of Belfast's office stock points towards an eventual pick-up
in demand for more development. 'We believe that developers who commence new
projects will be rewarded with rents significantly above current levels,'
says Lambert Smith Hampton, chartered surveyors.
New development is centred on derelict land by the river bank, which is
being developed by the Laganside Corporation with funds from the Department
of Environment of Northern Ireland. The corporation's first office
development is nearing completion but future phases are expected to proceed
slowly.
Confidence in Belfast property is at a low ebb, after a strong performance
during the 1980s. The average annual return between 1980 and 1991 was 16.5
per cent, compared with a UK average of 9.7 per cent, according to
Investment Property Databank, a research body.
Retail landlords did particularly well, with returns of nearly 20 per cent
in the 1980s, eight percentage points above the average for the UK. Rents
were boosted by a resurgence in retailing as UK retailers, previously
under-represented, moved into the province.
'Taking a seven- to 10-year view I have no doubt that Northern Ireland will
outperform the rest of the UK because there is less quality property,' says
Mr Tony O'Connor of Lambert Smith Hampton. 'But we are going to be in a
difficult period for the next 12 months.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IX
