<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (8): Markets succumb - The Midlands /
Confidence has evaporated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPERTY markets in the Midlands are not exactly bubbling and some have
succumbed to inertia since the post-election confidence - evident throughout
the economy - evaporated in June and July.
The East Midlands, said Mr Tony Hewitt, chief executive of Connell Wilson,
surveyors, 'withstood the storm better than most. But it desperately needs
some boost to the economy.' The East Midlands, he went on, is better than
the West Midlands and they are both better than the south-east of England.
Both Midlands regions have in common the fact that the retail sector is
flat. 'You only have to look at the agents' boards on a high street,' noted
Mr Hewitt. In the Birmingham area of the West Midlands, 'most retailers have
put plans on hold and are concentrating on survival,' according to
Chesterton, surveyors, although it observed that there is little vacant
space in the big shopping centres.
The office market is more complex, more varied. There has been some stimulus
in Nottingham because of planned government department relocations, notably
that of the Inland Revenue. Derby, too, is receiving 1,700 Prison Service
posts. Such relocations have prompted rivalries in the area, with Mansfield
District Council pointing out that average office rents in its area are
Pounds 8 a square foot compared with Pounds 12 in Nottingham, Lincoln,
Leicester and Derby and Pounds 16 in Northampton.
However, Mr Hewitt has noticed some slippage in Northampton rents for new
accommodation to more like Pounds 12-Pounds 13 a sq ft. The contrary is true
in central Birmingham, where, said Mr Roger Ford of Chesterton, rents are
stable and there are very few discounts.
'If you look at quality space - raised floors, air-conditioning and so on -
there is very little available. It's down to about 50,000 sq ft.' Rents are
steady at about Pounds 20 a sq ft. But office property , especially, in
small units, is freely available at much lower prices in the fringe areas of
the city.
On the industrial side of the West Midlands, there is a lot of what Mr Ford
called 'poor property' available, but not very much which is brand new.
Deals are being done, although. But both the East and West Midlands have a
firm market in large distribution sheds.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
