<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (7): Energy and drive - Wales / Cardiff
and Newport are expected to out-perform most other provincial areas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE MOIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE is no faulting the energy and drive of the Welsh Development Agency.
On the pretext of Columbus Day, London agents and journalists had been drawn
down to Newport to watch fireworks outside Columbus House, an office
development nearing completion by Midlands developers Wilson Bowden with
help from the WDA.
Then it was on to Cwmbran, a few miles away, where the WDA was relaunching
marketing for the renamed Brecon House, a high specification manufacturing
base abandoned by a departing US electronics company for whom it had been
designed in the mid-1980s.
The government agency and the developer were putting a good face on it, but
both buildings will be difficult to fill. The problem with Brecon House is
the very high specification of which it boasts. No one other than computer
manufacturers needs the sort of clean rooms Brecon House offers: and that
industry is contracting at present.
Columbus House, an altogether more standard 25,000 sq ft office block, faces
a different struggle: competition. The building is sensibly divisible into
four self-contained units, if necessary, and its location, alongside the M4
outside Newport, is sound. But the 55-acre Langstone Office Park which it
inaugurates faces competition from two other business parks in Newport:
Cleppa Park, which has already attracted tenants of the quality of TSB; and
Celtic Lakes, a massive planned 2m sq ft science and business park, of which
the core is the 50-acre Imperial Park for Imperial College with the WDA
among its joint venturers.
The WDA has a well deserved reputation for cajoling inward investment into
South Wales - to the tune of 100,000 jobs and Pounds 4.7bn of capital in the
past 10 years. But, notwithstanding top flight letting agents - Jones Lang
Wootton for Celtic Lakes and Debenham Tewson &amp; Chinnocks for Langstone Park
 -it will take Newport some time to absorb the space these schemes
represent.
Possibly because of the vigour of the WDA and its success in attracting big
overseas owner-occupiers, South Wales has not been seen as an attractive
region for institutional portfolio investment. But in a property recession
as severe as today's, that may be a blessing in disguise.
Jones Lang Wootton believes that rents in Cardiff, the premier location,
have fallen back from about Pounds 18 to Pounds 15-Pounds 16, with rent-free
periods a common feature. But that is a far cry from the 50 per cent drop in
Central London rents and the inducements to tenants are not so lavish.
As a business centre, Cardiff has still to see the full effects of its
docklands redevelopment. Legislation is still awaited before the Cardiff Bay
Barrage can go ahead, for example. Some of the more ambitious ideas - such
as a light railway linking town centre and bay along a Champs Elysee-style
boulevard - may be abandoned. But the scheme continues to attract interest
from investors and would-be tenants while avoiding the excesses which
undermined London's Docklands.
Outside the Cardiff Bay Development Corporation's area, however, the
presence of the WDA is vital for developments of any scale. Typical of its
new policy of partnership with the private sector is the 90-acre Cardiff
Gate business park at North Pentwyn. This involves DMD, a local developer,
and a civil engineering division of Fiat. It will provide extensive housing
and leisure facilities in addition to between 1m and 1.5m sq ft of business
space.
If that project has yet to show more than potential benefits, another WDA
initiative at the western end of the Newport-Cardiff axis is already well
into its second phase.
Bridgend has been transformed with the attraction of multinationals such as
Ford and Sony, both of which are planning local expansion despite
retrenchment elsewhere. Ford is putting Pounds 450m into its South Wales
plants and will build 350,000 Zeta engines at Bridgend. Sony is spending
Pounds 150m upgrading its Bridgend facilities and other technology-based
companies are prospecting in the area as part of the spin-off.
To the north of the favoured M4 corridor, prospects remain more mixed. Not
all the efforts of local authority and development body have been able to
guarantee the long-term commercial transformation of Ebbw Vale. One local
agent believes the 'footfall at the Garden Festival was lower than we hoped
and has produced few bankable proposals'.
In any case the commercial engine of the principality must be expected to
remain in the south-east. Cardiff and Newport are expected to out-perform
most other provincial areas from early in the upturn when it comes. The
Cardiff Bay Barrage should put the seal on the capital's regeneration and
Newport's prospects will further brighten with the opening of the second
Severn Bridge in 1996.
Meanwhile both continue to show exceptional defensive strengths at a time
when other areas have sagged noticeably with the steepening recession.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-7847</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKMB5AG1FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (6): Hardest to call - Industrials /
Victims of the double dip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE MOIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OF all the property sectors, industrials are probably the hardest to call at
present; it is possible that they have reached a watershed which in turn may
have indicated the arrival of the recession's second dip.
Until the summer, factories and warehouses were undoubtedly the best
performers in an otherwise grisly market.
That certainty has now vanished. Since mid-year, lettings and capital values
surveys have been out of date almost before publication.
During the third quarter, the number of investment transactions declined
significantly, according to Mr David Hutchings, head of investment research
at Healey &amp; Baker, although demand for well-let modern space continued.
But more telling may be the accelerating decline in rental levels seen in
the Hillier Paker rent index: -2.3 per cent between February and May,
accelerating to -3.2 per cent between May and August.
There is also little joy to be found in the most recent floorspace survey
from King &amp; Co. Throughout 1990 and 1991 the industrial sector was
underpinned by a relative balance between supply and normal demand -
relative, that is, to the grossly over-supplied office market. But there are
now signs that manufacturing and distribution companies are failing to mop
up space at the same rate.
King &amp; Co's figures to mid-August show a 4 per cent overall increase in
available floorspace to an historically high level of 163m sq ft in England
and Wales - and these figures were reached before the spate of autumn
closures and shrinkages announced by BAe, Ford and others, let alone the
knock-on effects of the government's attempt to halve British Coal.
There is still strength to be seen in the industrial sector. New buildings
continue to be taken up: their supply declined, according to King &amp; Co. But
they now make up 12 per cent of all stock, which suggests that the backlog
of second-hand stock will continue to mount, with increasing amounts
virtually unlettable.
Prospects for the fourth quarter look bleaker. A reduction of two percentage
points in interest rates between Black Wednesday and mid-October failed to
restore confidence in the government's handling of the economy.
Until this autumn northern regions had appeared relatively unscathed by the
recession and there was hope that they might lead the national recovery. But
the Northern Development Company and the Tyne and Wear and Teesside chambers
of commerce dashed those hopes.
Sales, orders, confidence and employment levels in Cumbria and the North
East have all dropped sharply and the position is worsening. Only 16 per
cent of companies are working close to capacity and nearly 90 per cent
believe the outlook is even blacker.
The depth of the UK market in industrial sheds is such, however, that deals
are still being done. Mr Guy Frampton, senior agency surveyor at Hillier
Parker, for example, reports signs of life in the M25 belt which has
stagnated for two years.
So far, evidence for new lease structures is only anecdotal. But it cannot
be long before it is made official. No property luncheon table is without
its tales of breaches of the traditional 25-year lease with upward-only rent
reviews.
As if there were not enough bad news about, another dismal trend is still
gathering pace: the knock-on effects of shrinkage in information technology
manufacturing. In itself, the 'downsizing' of IBM by 40,000 jobs with a
further 32,000 jobs gone or going at Compaq, Hewlett-Packard and Digital
Equipment would be bad enough. But the property industry may not yet have
taken on board the difficulty of finding replacement tenants for
highly-customised buildings designed to meet the specifications of high-tech
manufacturers.
Overall, the key to servicing depressed industrial tenants with poor sales
prospects as well as risk-averse investors seeking reliable income streams,
may lie with good, secondary properties: true, multi-purpose,
low-specification sheds on estates close to motorways.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-7848</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKMB5AG0FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (5): Is the industry over-reacting? -
London Office Market / In the deepest recession in memory, with a fifth of
central London's offices empty, the prospect of shortages is emerging
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LAWSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TWO bruised and battered birds symbolise the crisis in London's office
markets.
The canary is immediately recognisable as the label of that monolithic
Docklands tower block which typifies the heights of ambition reached during
the 1980s boom - only to crash into bankruptcy.
A semi-comatose duck in a sailor suit is more puzzling, yet it sums up just
as vividly what went wrong. In cartoons, Donald Duck rushes off a cliff and
is several steps into thin air before realising he is standing on thin air.
Then down he crashes.
Developers made the same mistake, building so hard and fast that they were
over the precipice before noticing that no-one was taking the space. Now
they lie broken on the ground.
'The recession started the day after Black Monday in 1987,' says Mr Geoff
Marsh of Applied Property Research. Net absorption turned negative a year
later - in other words new offices plus the old space that movers dump on
the market began to exceed demand. But no-one seemed to notice.
Even between mid-1990 and mid-1991, when demand had obviously collapsed and
vacancy rates were soaring, the flapping continued. Only 2.5m sq ft was
cancelled, according to consultants Debenham Tewson &amp; Chinnocks. Finally, in
the past 12 months, some 20m sq ft of potential development has been
scrapped.
Ironically, the industry may be over-reacting. In the deepest property
recession of living memory, with a fifth of central London's offices
standing empty and rents in free-fall, the prospect of shortages is
emerging. That sounds ludicrous when central London has a supply for between
10 and 15 years, yet certain types of space are running out.
Location and quality are important again, and there are gaps in the map of
prime space. Westminster, for example, has hardly more than a dozen or so
top-class blocks bigger than 50,000 sq ft - and almost as many leading
companies looking for that sort of space. The area could see supply and
demand balancing by the end of next year, says Mr Marsh.
Narrowing down further to the primest of prime areas - Mayfair and St
James's - only four new buildings of more than 25,000 sq ft are available,
says Mr Rupert Dodson of Healey &amp; Baker.
These quirks produce a wide spread of rent levels. Poorer second-hand space
was letting for Pounds 15 a sq ft or less in the three months to June while
prime was fetching Pounds 20 to Pounds 30, according to Jones Lang Wootton.
Yet Healey &amp; Baker and Nelson Bakewell extracted a reputed Pounds 55 a sq ft
from Cadbury Schweppes for a 50,000 sq ft Randsworth Trust block in Berkeley
Square, confirming that some buoyant companies will pay highly for quality
space in the right place.
The City of London might seem immune from shortages after vast
over-indulgence by developers during the boom. This left a vacancy rate
approaching 20 per cent and helped cut prime rents by 40 per cent to Pounds
37.50 a sq ft - not counting incentives which average an equivalent
three-year rent-free period.
Yet Mr Colin Hargreaves of Healey &amp; Baker predicts a 'material shortage' in
the core EC2 area by next year. Mr Gareth Davies at Grimley J R Eve picks
out potential problems in finding new, high-quality units of 1,000-3,000 sq
ft because 1980s buildings were designed for large-floor users.
At the other end of the scale, movers would be hard-pressed to find anything
over 250,000 sq ft for a new headquarters since MEPC stole Chemical Bank
away from Canary Wharf to take half of Alban Gate.
Numerous blocks in between are the real problem. Many are so old, badly
designed or poorly located that some may never find a tenant.
But they help contribute to a total central London stock which Edward Erdman
Research calculates would require a 25 per cent expansion in the workforce
to fill.
Even the more realistic target of reaching 'manageable' vacancy rates of 5
or 6 per cent would require the replacement of all 100,000 jobs lost since
the end of 1989.
This seems unlikely when the Confederation of British Industry (CBI) is
predicting 30,000 financial services job losses by the end of this year and
the latest Jones Lang Wootton Business Confidence review shows 20,000 office
jobs will disappear across the whole south-east in the next 12 months. JLW
also predicts total demand for only 3.7m sq ft for the whole region, a third
of which is pre-let and a quarter being built for owner-occupation.
But Mr Gerry Blundell of JLW finds a bright spot in the West End, where
potential demand has soared.
Mr Marsh also sees openings for developers, because land held at historic or
nil cost - which must take in many central London pitches - can yield a
juicy return of 14.5 per cent on a 50,000 sq ft block at rents of only
Pounds 25 a sq ft.
That presupposes finding a tenant to pay this modest amount, although this
may not be over-ambitious if lower interest rates manage to kick-start the
economy.
In the City of London alone, KFR Research found almost 30 per cent of
tenants wanted to expand into new premises and were held back only because
they could not shake off existing space or new buildings were not good
enough. In fact, Healey &amp; Baker estimates there is pent-up demand for nearly
9m sq ft of City space - about three years' average net absorption.
This is the invisible thread holding up developers still building in London.
Whether they are revealed as Donald Ducks remains to be seen but they must
be looking down nervously at the dead ducks lying broken and bloody below.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
