<DOCNO>FT924-7851</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKMB5AGXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (2): The search for a reliable income -
Investment and finance / Net investments by life companies in the first six
months of this year amounted to only Pounds 424m. And inward investment from
foreign buyers has slowed to a trickle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE MOIR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Alan Winter, managing director of Legal &amp; General's property arm, is
quietly pleased with the performance of his portfolio. Even in central
London lettings are being achieved: last week for example, British Rail took
42,000 sq ft in Euston House.
The latest industrial development - the Campus Estate in Hemel Hempstead -
has also just become fully let, with the last 25,000 sq ft unit going to
Modern Alarms.
Of the eight shopping centres owned by the life company, only one has spaces
of more than 5 per cent - and that is a new development in Ipswich open for
trading only since the beginning of October.
The most recent retail investment purchase - the Grange shopping centre in
Birkenhead, bought for Pounds 24m in October to show a 12 per cent return -
is 100 per cent let.
In today's market, such a smooth performance has not been achieved without
cost.
Early this year Legal &amp; General decided to cut asking rents across the board
even though it had not pushed them up as aggressively as others during the
boom years of the mid-1980s.
The result, says Mr Winter, is that 'rents are now broadly supported by
today's trading levels.'
Unlike most of his competitors, therefore, Mr Winter is actively buying
properties in the market (although not, it must be said, London offices) and
he expects to invest a total of Pounds 350m in property this year with
further net investment in 1993.
Investment statistics for the market as a whole show this strategy to be
markedly against the trend; net investments by life companies in the first
six months of this year amounted to only Pounds 424m compared with Pounds
1.48bn for the whole of 1991.
Pension funds were even more reluctant buyers, putting Pounds 189m into the
market compared with Pounds 564m.
And inward investment from foreign buyers has slowed to a trickle.
Legal &amp; General finds itself in the fortunate position of being able to hunt
bargains in this weak market having sold Pounds 800m of property at the peak
of the market in 1989 and 1990. This reduced the percentage of property in
the main life fund from the high 20s to just under 16 - at the bottom of the
15-20 per cent range which Mr Winter now believes to be a comfortable
long-term benchmark for a large fund.
Despite the deliberate contra-cyclical approach, Mr Winter's choice of
purchases does offer pointers to the market. Erstwhile prime property does
not appeal: the target is higher yield - industrial and retail warehousing
at about 9.5 per cent; land banks for the future even if presently covered
by poor quality buildings; and shopping centres on yields as high as 12 per
cent.
Developments are a thing of the past; Legal &amp; General has run down its
development team from 30-strong in 1989 to just five and it is unlikely to
volunteer for fresh development schemes before the end of the decade.
The search for reliable income streams has been a feature of the investment
market for two years and now favours the industrial sector because it has
suffered less than offices from speculative over-building. But, in an
ominous sign, third-quarter yields on industrial units moved above 9 per
cent; a symptom of the fall-off in manufacturing demand which seems set to
accelerate into the final quarter. According to agents Healey &amp; Baker, only
a few choice distribution centres can now fetch 9.25 per cent; less than
prime estates are touching 10 per cent.
The retail investments market has also turned soggy again, although the
necessarily limited supply of top locations has sustained prices for the
very best high street units even without prospects for rental growth. Healey
&amp; Baker confirm that most interest is being shown in smaller investments -
under Pounds 5m - and smaller towns and market centres.
The less said about central London offices the better: over-supply and
over-renting are the market's two main nightmares. But in all areas and
sectors medium-term prospects continue to deteriorate and perhaps only the
largest funds with no liquidity problems can afford to take a sufficiently
long-term view.
That certainly does not apply to most property developers. Forced to abandon
speculation, those in a position to do so are busy repaying borrowings.
Bank of England figures show that total borrowing by property companies fell
by 5.2 per cent in the 12 months to May and total outstanding bank advances
in May were Pounds 38.6bn, down 1.6 per cent since February.
These figures show just how long it will take to bear down on the excesses
of the 1980s. The shallow decline in bank lending revealed in the Band of
England figures represents, according to Jones Lang Wootton, net repayments
of Pounds 1bn in the first half of this year. Property companies will be
occupied with repaying loans for many years yet.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page III
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-7852</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKMB5AGWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Guide to UK Property (1): A growing list of failures -
Overview / Tenants' bankruptcies have added to industry problems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEW areas of British industry have suffered so visibly during the recession
as the UK property industry. This year, its declining fortunes became
obvious to even the most casual observer.
In place of the trappings of the boom - the duckboards, cranes, dust and
traffic diversions - there are now derelict, boarded-up buildings, unlet new
developments and rows of letting signs.
The ever-growing list of failures has embraced property companies, shopping
centres and office developments, most notably the ill-starred Canary Wharf
development that towers over East London.
The problems of the property industry are no longer merely those of its own
making. Even where it did not overvalue, overbuild and over-borrow, it has
suffered from record bankruptcies among tenants.
The industrial sector, for example, has suffered heavily from the recession
this year, even though it never became oversupplied with new buildings.
Not every participant in the property market is despondent, however. Tenants
who are unencumbered with existing premises have had opportunities to sign
cheap leases on their own terms.
Some fledgling retail companies have expanded rapidly in underlet shopping
centres with the help of incentives from desperate landlords.
Some investors, too, are cheered by the opportunity to buy at what they
perceive as the bottom of the market.
Their enthusiasm is whetted by the very high level of property yields, which
this year exceeded gilt yields for the first time since the 1960s.
Many also believe that the dearth of new construction activity will bring
the property market back into balance in a few years' time.
The state of the market is very uneven. Pockets of the market such as retail
warehouses and supermarkets have largely escaped the downturn. The decline
has not affected every part of the UK. In Scotland, for example, rents
actually rose in the year to September.
Even the depressed Central London office market shows large variations in
the severity of the downturn.
While top rents have generally halved since their peak in May 1990 to Pounds
35 per sq ft at most, the scarcity of large modern buildings in the West End
recently led Cadbury Schweppes, the confectionery and soft drinks group, to
pay a reported Pounds 55 per sq ft for a building in Berkeley Square.
Record vacancy rates should not be taken entirely at face value. Herring
Baker Harris, chartered surveyors, says that 5m sq ft of offices in the City
of London, where 20 per cent of offices are empty, are virtually unlettable
space.
The prospects for some office blocks are so poor that their owners are
making them uninhabitable to escape the burden of rates bills.
Even modern buildings do not necessarily provide the premises that occupiers
want. A study by Debenham Tewson &amp; Chinnocks, property advisers, showed that
speculative developments often did not meet tenants' needs.
'While the development boom has affected most key office centres, this
should not be taken to mean that the choice available to potential office
occupiers has increased in line with construction activity,' it concluded.
Despite these caveats, the unprecedented imbalance between supply and demand
is putting new power in the hands of tenants seeking new space. This - and
the difficulties of letting and selling buildings - is changing the roles of
banks, developers and investors.
The developers are being kept afloat by their bankers for the present while
they attempt to let their existing buildings. But they are under heavy
pressure to cut costs and their future prospects look bleak.
There is little prospect of attracting finance for future speculative
developments as the banks are only prepared to provide property finance in
the most exacting circumstances. The banks' reluctance stems from the scale
of their existing problems, which has made them, in effect, the unwilling
owners of property for years to come.
The attitude of investors has also changed. The old adage was that all that
mattered in property was 'location, location, location.' The emphasis has
changed to stress the quality of the covenant above the location and the
quality of property.
The pressures mounting on the traditional lease is perhaps the most dramatic
symptom of the new conditions facing developers, investors and tenants.
Tenants, particularly retailers, are baulking at the 25-year lease with
upwards-only reviews every five years, which they see as restrictive and
inflationary. Landlords are being forced to concede break clauses that allow
the tenant to curtail the lease prematurely. Similarly, tenants have lobbied
intensely for a change in the law on privity of contract, which allows
landlords to reclaim unpaid rent from former tenants, where a lease has been
assigned.
Investors are anxiously watching the pressure for change to lease
structures. Many institutional investors feel that any change would be a
severe threat to the security of income from property. As a result, the role
of property in institutional portfolios could be jeopardised by reform.
The role of property in institutional portfolio is under scrutiny for other
reasons, too. The UK's withdrawal from the European Monetary System's
exchange rate mechanism has reopened the debate about property's role as a
hedge against inflation.
Even those who believe that inflation will not re-emerge as a serious
problem generally believe that property's prospects have been boosted by the
exit from the ERM. It allowed a relaxation of high real interest rates,
which bore down heavily on indebted property companies.
It remains to be seen whether institutional interest in commercial property
can be rekindled. Net institutional property investment remained subdued
this year, totalling just Pounds 212m in the second quarter, according to
the Central Statistical Office. In some parts of the market, such as the
City of London, the institutions' involvement was exceeded by overseas
investors.
Buying interest, from whatever source, has been highly selective. It is
focused on well-let, well-located and high quality property that makes up,
at most, a fifth of the market.
The bulk of the investment market will only begin its recovery after tenants
stop going bankrupt and start to absorb new space. Even if the decline
abates, few analysts expect any significant improvement in the coming year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page II
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-7853</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CKMB5AGVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Survey of Japan and the European Community (15) Parisian
showcase links two cultures - Shiseido, a powerful player in the
international cosmetics industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE are few parts of Paris that are quite as French as the Palais Royal,
the sumptuous squares and arched arcades built by Cardinal Richelieu in the
17th century and now colonised by such Parisian institutions as Jack Lang's
arts ministry and the Grand Vefour, one of the oldest and finest restaurants
in the city.
Hidden in the arches is a prettily painted shop with astrological symbols
and animal images sketched on its walls in different shades of purple and
elegantly-shaped flasks of perfume in the windows. This is the Haute
Parfumerie opened earlier this year by Shiseido, the Japanese company which
is one of the most powerful players in the international cosmetics industry,
as a showcase for its European interests.
Shiseido spent more than Dollars 2m to create its Haute Parfumerie. It sells
its perfumes from the shop, but sees it less as a regular retail outlet than
as an extension of its publicity programme along the lines of the lavish
beauty salons owned by the established French fragrance houses, Guerlain and
Boucheron.
The Haute Parfumerie also marks the latest stage of Shiseido's expansion in
Europe. Shiseido first ventured into Europe in the early 1960s, when it
started selling its products in Italy. It formalised its Italian links in
1968 by setting up Shiseido Cosmetics (Italia) as its first European
subsidiary.
Italy was used as a testing ground throughout the 1970s - 'in the early days
we treated the Italian operation very much as an experiment,' says Mr Yukata
Goto, chief executive of Shiseido International (France). 'And we learnt a
lot from our experience there."
In 1980 Shiseido was ready to launch a fully-fledged assault on the European
market, where it faced strong competition from indigenous companies,
including L'Oreal of France, as well as the US groups, Revlon and Estee
Lauder. The group set up new subsidiaries in France, Germany and, later, in
the UK.
Shiseido also introduced specially developed versions of all its ranges  -
perfumes, skin care products and cosmetics - for the European market. Its
Italian experience had demonstrated that it could not expect to sell the
same formulae in Europe as in its native Japan.
'The demands of European consumers are different for every product type,'
said Mr Goto. 'The Japanese tend to prefer lighter, more subtle fragrances
than the Europeans. There are also differences in skin types and in the
climate, which is much more humid in Japan.'
Similarly Shiseido decided to adopt a different approach to marketing. In
1980 it appointed Serge Lutens, a French designer and stylist, as its
international image creator. He has since co-ordinated every aspect of its
publicity across different international markets ranging from its
advertising campaigns to the decoration of the Palais Royal salon.
But until recently Shiseido shipped its specially developed European ranges
over from its factories in Japan and the US. This year it opened its first
European production plant, a factory at Gien in France.
SHISEIDO now directly employs 700 in Europe, where it made sales of Dollars
134m in its last financial year, an increase of 17 per cent on the previous
year. This means that Europe now represents 30 per cent of its sales outside
Japan, or 3.3 per cent of the group's overall Dollars 4.06bn turnover. This
means that Europe now plays a pivotal part in Shiseido's attempts to
increase its overall share of the international cosmetics market from 11 per
cent to 15 per cent by the year 2000.
Shiseido plans to concentrate on expanding its distribution, rather than
manufacturing, activities in Europe. The opening of the Haute Parfumerie in
the Palais Royal forms part of this strategy being, as Yoshiharu Fukuhara,
Shiseido's worldwide chief executive, put it, 'an ideal bridge linking our
two cultures.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
