<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / London Stock Exchange: Building sector supported
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE were no real shocks for a building and contracting sector already
primed to expect positive moves in the Autumn Statement. The building
sectors have been outperforming the wider market since the prime minister
outlined the government's strategy for growth last month.
Commenting on confirmation of the go-ahead for the Jubilee Line extension
and the expanded road building programme, a specialist at one of the leading
London broking firms said he expected the market might well be slightly
disappointed at the outcome. Among the building material groups, Redland
picked up 8 to 387p, Rugby 5 to 218p and RMC 13 to 515p.
The Jubilee extension go-ahead gave a big boost to John Mowlem, with its big
exposure to Docklands, and left the shares 6 higher at 89p. The move also
lifted Costain 1 1/2 to 31p and George Wimpey 4 to 106p. Other contractors
to move sharply higher included Alfred McAlpine, 15 better at 135p, and
Higgs &amp; Hill, which put on 2 1/2 at 45p.
Housebuilders were broadly higher, responding to the cut in interest rates.
Wilson Bowden jumped 19 to 339p, additionally helped by their inclusion in
the influential County-30 list of best buys. Bryant, the Midlands-based
housebuilder, gained 4 at 85p after the company's pension scheme sold a
block of 2.54m shares at 93p apiece. Most of the stock was quickly placed in
the market at 94p. A further block of 750,000 Bryant shares was crossed at
94p.
BTR hit
Industrial conglomerate BTR was an early exception to a very firm market as
securities house Kleinwort Benson took a harsh look at its previous profit
forecasts for the group. Coincidentally, BTR's share price had achieved an
all-time high on Wednesday.
Kleinwort analyst Mr Andrew Hollins refused to comment on figures being
quoted by rivals, but there was a strong belief that he had cut his 1992
profits estimate to Pounds 984m from Pounds 1.03bn and, more significantly,
his 1993 forecast to some Pounds 1.035bn from Pounds 1.15bn.
This year's figure was within the current range of estimates but next year's
is below most forecasts. Kleinwort is believed to have revised its view
after having seen trading figures for September. However, many felt the 1993
estimate was unnecessarily low considering the positive effect of currency
movements on a group that earns 40 per cent of its profits in Australia and
the US.
Also, the house reached its decision without talking to the company and BTR
was said to be 'unhappy' at the situation, particularly as it has been
talking extensively to other analysts recently. BTR shares closed 12 1/2
down at 494 1/2 p with 4.9m traded.
Shell acclaimed
Shell Transport's third-quarter results found widespread acclaim and the
shares raced higher in heavy trading. Replacement cost profits of Pounds
824m were well in excess of a comparable Pounds 523m and the market
forecasts which ranged from Pounds 575m to Pounds 685m. At their best Shell
touched 553p, before slipping to end a busy session a net 12 higher at 549p.
Turnover was a hefty 9.5m shares.
Many analysts said the results were boosted by various items. At County
NatWest, Mr Fergus Macleod said: 'The more I looked, the less impressed I
was; 30 per cent of the profits came from non-operating earnings. The shares
look expensive.' Mr Nick Clayton at Smith New Court described Shell shares
as 'very good value for the long-term', and pointed out that the company had
reduced net debt by Pounds 750m during the quarter, leaving gearing at only
5 per cent.
Mr John Toalster at Strauss Turnbull said Shell's figures 'continue to
vindicate our long term recommendation to switch out of BP into Shell; they
show how much stronger a company it is compared with BP.' The latter edged
up 2 to 238p on 9.5m traded.
Gloomy comments at a lunch with its broker prompted a sharp fall for the
share price of Arjo Wiggins Appleton. The stock dropped 10 to 156p - one of
the biggest percentage falls in London yesterday - as the post-prandial mood
leaked into the market.
Arjo executives told broker UBS Phillips &amp; Drew that when it decided to cut
its dividend two months ago it had done so on an 18-month view of life not
getting any easier. Also, the UBS media team, which has the stock as a
'hold' recommendation, is believed to be reconsidering its current forecast
of Pounds 185m for 1992.
A strong set of final figures from Burton sent the shares smartly forward,
but left analysts sharply divided over the future prospects of the
recovering stores group.
Revised profits forecasts for next year ranged from Pounds 15m (Kleinwort
Benson) to Pounds 32 1/2 m (Nomura), with bears of the stock still wary of
the group's ability to deliver sustained profits growth, given its recent
track record.
County NatWest turned from a seller to a short-term hold of the stock,
welcoming the improved sales growth and maintained dividend. However,
analyst Ms Kimlan Cook said the long-term performance of the shares remained
in doubt. 'Burton still has a long way to go before it achieves an
acceptable return on sales,' she added.
The stock, which was the most heavily traded yesterday, jumped 11 to 55p in
turnover of 25m shares. Dealers said the temperature was additionally raised
by a story that joint-broker Cazenove had lifted its 1993/94 profits
estimate to Pounds 70m, practically double the average for the rest of the
market. Cazenove refused to comment on the rumour.
Leading pharmaceutical stocks performed well on the back of rises on Wall
Street the previous day. Glaxo gained 8 to 816p, SmithKline Beecham rose 16
to 530p and Wellcome advanced 6 to 984p.
Fisons retreated 7 to 214p, pushed back by position-taking between
marketmakers.
Hammerson stood out in a muted property sector as other brokers joined the
recent bout of upgrading of its net asset value. The ordinary shares moved
ahead 16 to 254p and the 'A' stock ended 14 stronger at 249p.
In spite of satisfactory interim results, Boots retreated in busy turnover
of 3.6m on a combination of profit-taking, US drug worries and hints that
current trading may be getting tougher. The shares, which lost 10 yesterday
to 487p, had run up ahead of the results, moving close to the top of their
trading range. Boots also suffered as a perceived defensive stock, as did
Great Universal Stores, which weakened 23 to 1635p.
Publisher Euromoney produced profits well above the high end of expectations
and the shares jumped 32 to 890p. SG Warburg believes that even at this
level there is strong upside and argues that on its 1993 forecast of Pounds
14.5m the shares are a buy up to Pounds 10.
BT shares appreciated 15 to 388p and the partly-paid 16 to 284p after the
second-quarter figures. The rise in the shares, according to specialists,
reflected the increased turnover in call volumes and a reduction in costs.
Royal Insurance rose 19 to 245p after better than expected third-quarter
results.
A bearish note published by Panmure Gordon, the stockbroker, was said to
have triggered the substantial underperformance of the banking sector
against the wider market.
Plastics manufacturer Plysu fell 22 to 243p after a boardroom resignation.
BAA lost 9 to 749p, with Kleinwort Benson said to be negative after the
publication of the most recent passenger figures.
Motor distributors received a fillip from the announcement in the Autumn
Statement about car tax. Lex Service advanced 18 to 244p, Jessups improved 8
to 73p and Evans Halshaw rose 10 to 189p.
NEW HIGHS AND LOWS FOR 1992
NEW HIGHS (136).
BRITISH FUNDS (8) Tr. 8pc '02-06, Tr. 8 1/2 pc '07, Tr. 9pc '08, Cv. 9pc
'11, Tr. 9pc '12, Do A, Tr. 5 1/2 pc '08-12, Tr. 7 3/4 pc '12-15, OTHER
