<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NERVOUS futures market saw a mostly firm day's trading turn into a late
slide as traders declared themselves disappointed with the chancellor's
statement, writes Christopher Price.
The December contract opened at 2,729 and was squeezed up from thereon in
anticipation of some tangible signs from the government that growth policies
would be pursued. The contract peaked around lunchtime at 2,765 - a new
contract high - before nerves set in and a bout of sideways trading
followed.
However, the chancellor's speech failed to impress the market, with most
measures announced already discounted, according to traders.
December began to tumble, eventually closing at 2,745, up 28 from the
previous day and at a slight premium to its fair value of around 17. In
after-hours' trading, December came under more pressure, with traders
forecasting a weak opening this morning. Its fair value range had peaked at
17 during the day, before narrowing in late selling. Turnover was 8,265
lots.
In the traded options market, volume was a substantial 40,377 contracts, of
which 10,275 was in the FT-SE 100 option. ASDA once again led the way with
9,201.
This was followed by Land Securities, which saw 1,200 July 420 calls sold at
23p. Thames Water, on 2,306, and Scottish Power, on 1,970, were other
sizeable trades.
</TEXT>
