<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / World Stock Markets (America): Retailers feature as Dow
loses early gain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US SHARE prices failed to find their footing as the market gave up its early
gains and ended the day virtually unchanged, writes Karen Zagor in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average was finally off 0.54 at 3,239.79. New York
SE volume was fairly heavy at 226m shares, while rises retained a small lead
over declines by 901 to 862. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 was just 0.67 up on
balance at 422.87 and the Nasdaq composite, which has outpaced the wider
market in recent sessions, lost 0.55 at 634.37.
The day's economic news proved unexceptional for both stocks and bonds.
Jobless claims for the week ended October 31 fell 5,000 to 355,000.
Investors had been looking for an increase of about 10,000.
The figures initially boosted stocks and depressed bonds, lifting long-term
market interest rates, but they failed to make a lasting impression on
either, and by midsession prices were narrowly mixed in both markets. Bond
prices moved higher in late trading following a successful refunding
auction.
Third-quarter results lifted The Gap Dollars 2 3/8 to Dollars 33 5/8 after
the clothing chain posted net income in line with analysts' expectations.
The Limited, which reported slightly higher net income earlier this week,
slipped Dollars 1/4 to Dollars 23 3/4 . Land's End fell Dollars 5 5/8 to a
52-week low of Dollars 24 1/4 on flat third-quarter profits after
expectations of a substantial improvement.
Federated Department Stores, which announced greatly improved third-quarter
results on Wednesday, ended Dollars  1/2 higher at Dollars 17 3/8 after
active trading.
Vons, a West Coast supermarket chain, advanced Dollars 1 to Dollars 24 1/8
after revealing third-quarter net income of 51 cents a share. A year ago the
company had earnings of 42 cents that included extraordinary gains of 10
cents.
Union Texas Petroleum was the most active issue on the big board after
Allied-Signal said it would sell 30m shares of the company for Dollars 18
1/4 apiece. The stock closed at Dollars 18 1/2 , up Dollars  1/8 on the day.
Pharmaceutical issues continued to rally as the sector recovered from
earlier fears that a Clinton administration would immediately curb drug
prices. Merck, the biggest US drug company, led NYSE trading and put on
Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 45 3/4 , Abbott Laboratories rose Dollars  3/8 to
Dollars 29 3/4 and Pfizer firmed Dollars  1/8 to Dollars 77 1/4 . Glaxo
Holdings, however, dipped Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 24 3/4 .
Canada
TORONTO stocks ended mixed after moderately active dealings. The TSE 300
index shed 2.6 to 3,283.8 and volume amounted to 28.8m shares valued at
CDollars 317.4m. Advances led declines by 283 to 268.
The real estate sector index showed the biggest swing among the sub-groups,
falling 2.98 per cent. Conglomerates were down 2.38 per cent and mining lost
1.38 per cent.
