<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Irish Company News: Bank of Ireland jumps 69% as US and UK
losses are reduced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BANK OF Ireland, the Republic's second largest clearing bank, yesterday
reported a 69 per cent jump in pre-tax profits to IPounds 65.8m (Pounds
72.4m) in the half year to September 30, up from IPounds 38.6m at the
interim stage last time.
Mr Paul D'Alton, group financial officer, said 80 per cent of the
improvement had come through loss reductions in the bank's US and UK
divisions, while the 20 per cent growth in income to IPounds 409m was
largely a result of the incorporation of last year's acquisitions of
Amoskeag and BankEast banks in the US, into its First New Hampshire
subsidiary.
Retail profits in Ireland advanced 15 per cent to IPounds 70.6m, while those
from corporate and treasury operations rose 18 per cent to IPounds 35.2m. UK
losses were reduced by 48 per cent to IPounds 5.3m, while losses at FHN were
cut back by 22 per cent to IPounds 27.3m.
Mr Pat Molloy, group chief executive, said: 'We have had solid performance
in our Irish-based business, and given the prevailing market conditions we
believe we have done very well.' He said business prospects in the UK 'were,
and still are very bleak", while any improvements in the US market 'will be
very gradual and are not very perceptible'.
The bank has writen down 'to a realistic value' its 940,000 shares in GPA
Group, the aircraft lessor in talks with its bankers. Mr D'Alton declined to
give the new value of its 0.41 per cent stake but said 'Any further
write-down will not have a material impact on our results'.
Loan loss provisions have been held at IPounds 72m (IPounds 70.4m), of which
IPounds 42.6m relates to the New Hampshire market and collapse in property
values there. Mr D'Alton said the bank had decided 'to grasp the nettle' in
making, from the IPounds 42.6m, a IPounds 21.6m provision for market decline
there.
Hilco, an FNH subsidiary to which its problem property debts have been
transferred, has had the carrying value of its repossessed properties
reduced from Dollars 100m (Pounds 66.2m) to Dollars 21m by sales and
write-downs, and which includes an additional Dollars 50m in transfers over
the past year from FNH's books.
Mr Molloy said he was not 'particularly pessimistic' about current high
interest rates in Ireland. 'If these persist, however, then that has to be
worrying.'
An unchanged interim dividend of 3.33p is declared out of earnings per share
up 34 per cent at 7.1p.
COMMENT
Bank of Ireland's ill-timed foray into the New Hampshire banking market in
1988 has cost it well over Dollars 500m in losses and write-offs, but there
are hopeful signs that the corner has been turned. The millstone of FNH's
failed property loans is being lightened, while rationalisation and
acquisition of new plug-on retail banking assets in the New Hampshire market
gives FNH a commanding 25 per cent market share with a wholly renovated loan
portfolio. Good domestic retail performance and well-run treasury operations
during the September currency crisis have made a strong contribution this
time round. The only real worry is whether high interest rates will push the
Irish economy into recession next year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 31
</PAGE>
