<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / UK Company News: FKI improves 19% to Pounds 16m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FKI, the electrical engineering group, reversed its profits decline with a
19 per cent interim increase from Pounds 13.5m to Pounds 16m before tax.
Four of its five divisions made progress and interest costs were cut.
The share price gained 6p to close at 88p, the highest level since early
1990.
A year ago FKI announced the halving of its interim pre-tax profit and
dividend and the resignation of its chief executive. The board has since
been strengthened by the recruitment as managing director of Mr Bob Beeston
from BTR.
Turnover in the six months to September 30 fell from Pounds 371.1m to Pounds
332.2m, while operating profit reached Pounds 18.8m (Pounds 18.5m). The
previous year's figures included Pounds 20.1m sales and Pounds 800,000
profit arising from different rates of exchange; 53 per cent of sales lie in
North America. Ongoing businesses raised their operating profit contribution
from Pounds 16.7m to Pounds 18.8m at constant exchange rates. Interest costs
fell from Pounds 5m to Pounds 2.8m. Debt was cut from Pounds 60m in March to
Pounds 50m in September.
Mr Beeston has set a target of getting a 10 per cent return on sales across
the group. He said that an average of 9.6 per cent had been achieved at
subsidiaries accounting for nearly two thirds of sales. 'We have to get the
rest right.'
Process control was the only division to go backwards with operating profit
falling from Pounds 5.87m to Pounds 3.7m on sales of Pounds 82.5m (Pounds
95.6m). It included two loss-makers in computer peripherals and cutting
tools.
Material handling improved profit from Pounds 3.56m to Pounds 4.54m on sales
of Pounds 82m (Pounds 85.8m). Two North American loss-makers had been
brought back to profit. One area of concern was British Coal's pit closure
plan which could cost Pounds 8m sales next year.
Hardware, virtually all in North America, improved operating profit by 10
per cent to Pounds 7.1m in spite of adverse exchange rates on same-again
sales of Pounds 62.5m.
The automotive division was returned to a Pounds 218,000 profit from a
Pounds 614,000 loss on Pounds 62.8m (Pounds 66.7m) sales. It had suffered
some disruption after factory closures but should experience a better second
half, Mr Beeston said. Engineering, UK-based and mainly supplying niche
markets, raised profit by Pounds 1m to Pounds 3.2m with the help of export
growth.
Earnings per share rose to 2.65p (2.2p) and the interim dividend goes up to
1.2p (1p).
COMMENT
Results at the top end of expectations and a welcome revival of the dividend
confirmed the view that the revamped management has taken the group by the
scruff of the neck. It still has its work cut out to increase operating
margins from less than 6 to 10 per cent, and further refining of the group
through disposals is part of the plan. The itch to acquire is also there,
although the paint is still a bit wet on the new-found credibility to allow
it to do anything big just yet. Signs of recovery in the US should help
progress to continue. Pre-tax profit is forecast to recover from Pounds
30.5m to Pounds 37m-Pounds 38m for the full year, giving a prospective p/e
of just over 14 which looks about right after a substantial re-rating this
year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 31
</PAGE>
