<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / BT falls 36% in wake of redundancies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGO DIXON and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BIG redundancy programme was behind a 36 per cent fall in British
Telecommunications' pre-tax profits for the half year to the end of
September.
Profits fell from Pounds 1.61bn to Pounds 1.03bn and earnings per share were
42 per cent down from 17.4p to 10.1p.
However, if redundancy charges of Pounds 442m and a Pounds 135m exceptional
loss incurred on the disposal of its Canadian Mitel subsidiary are added
back, earnings per share would have fallen only 2 per cent.
BT has cut its workforce by 35,300 since the start of the financial year and
expects to trim its 175,000 workforce by a further 15,000 a year over the
next two years.
The interim dividend will be 6.15p (5.7p), a 7.9 per cent increase. BT's
shares closed up 15p at 388p.
Mr Iain Vallance, BT's chairman, said the recession, regulation and tougher
competition led to a 1.5 per cent fall in turnover to Pounds 6.53bn. But in
the second quarter 'the first signs of a slight improvement may have been
perceptible' and this had continued in October.
On a 12-month moving average, inland call volumes fell 1 per cent,
international volumes grew 5 per cent and exchange line connections
increased 0.9 per cent.
Mr Vallance said of the link this week between Mercury Communications, its
main UK rival, and BCE, the Canadian telecommunications group: 'I am fairly
relieved at the choice of partner.'
He dismissed stockbroker suggestions that shareholder value could be
enhanced by increasing dividends more sharply or buying back the company's
shares.
Mr Barry Romeril, finance director, said such suggestions were based on the
hypothesis that the company would accumulate a cash mountain whereas its net
debt was more than Pounds 2bn.
Mr Vallance defended last week's sale of BT's stake in McCaw Cellular
Communications, the large US mobile communications company, as 'not a
strategic blow'.
He said that in the UK BT would like to provide entertainment services over
its network and integrate its mobile communications operations with its
mainstream network. Both are prevented by regulation.
Capital expenditure fell from Pounds 1.17bn to Pounds 952m.
Lex, Page 16
