<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / Ford names president in reshuffle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FORD MOTOR yesterday named Mr Alex Trotman president and chief operating
officer of its worldwide vehicle operations in a top management reshuffle
which left a question mark over the succession to Mr Harold Poling, the US
group's chairman and chief executive, who will retire next year.
The shake-up stems from yesterday's announcement that Mr Philip Benton, the
group's 63-year-old president and chief operating officer, will retire on
January 1. No date has been announced for the retirement of Mr Poling, 67,
though he said yesterday it would be late in 1993.
Mr Benton's title disappears under the shake-up while the top management
team - the office of the chief executive - is expanded from four members to
six.
The reshuffle places 59-year-old Mr Trotman, previously head of North
American car operations, in a much stronger position in the succession
stakes. Many analysts now expect him to get the top job rather than Mr Allan
Gilmour, 58.
Mr Poling said yesterday the changes were part of a smooth succession plan
and that an heir-apparent had already been selected, though he declined to
name him.
Mr Trotman rose on the operations side of the automotive business while Mr
Gilmour's experience has been mainly financial. Mr Trotman is the only
senior Ford executive to have run its vehicles operations in each of the
company's main markets - North America, Europe and Asia. He also becomes a
member of the board and office of the chief executive.
</TEXT>
