<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Details: 2.5% rise in NHS patient
capacity - Health
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NHS in England will be able to increase the number of patients it treats
next year by over 2.5 per cent, Mrs Virginia Bottomley, Secretary of State
for Health, said yesterday.
'That means an extra 190,000 acute in and day patients and one million extra
patient contacts by community nurses, taking the total number of patients
treated to its highest ever level,' she said in a statement.
'This increase in services is the result of the extra funds which have been
announced today for the NHS next year and of the efficiency improvements
which we expect the service to make.
'The Government is providing more than Pounds 1bn extra for health services
in England next year - a real terms increase of 3 per cent over our original
plans for 1992-93, or of one per cent over forecast outturn, equivalent to
about 1.8 per cent after taking account of the effects of the measures on
pay restraint which the Chancellor has announced today. That means the total
increase in Government spending on the NHS in England since we embarked on
our NHS reforms in 1989-90 will be over Pounds 9bn, or 17.7 per cent in real
terms. Between 1979 and now, Government spending on the NHS has grown by
57.6 per cent in real terms; we have increased nurses' pay by 51.6 per cent
after inflation, and doctors' pay by 33.6 per cent. This Government has
treated the NHS well: providing more resources and the means for them to be
put to best use. The announcement today shows the high priority we continue
to attach to the NHS.
'Pounds 800 million of the new money for next year which has been announced
today will go to the services provided by trusts and other hospitals and
community units. The extra money will be used for the benefit of both
patients and health service staff, by:
Maintaining the momentum of the health reforms and ensuring that money
continues to be used to the maximum benefit of patients;
Reducing waiting times by building on our successful Patients' Charter
targets;
Providing extra support for community health services so that the NHS can
play its part in implementing Caring for People;
Continuing to give emphasis to health promotion as well as treatment of
disease;
Making further progress on reducing junior doctors' working hours and
providing more Project 2000 training for nurses.
'These sums are in addition to the Pounds 539m which I have already
announced will be provided to local authorities next year to implement
Caring for People.'
</TEXT>
