<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Details: Shortfall in fund will be
met by Exchequer grant - National Insurance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHORTFALL in the National Insurance Fund will be met by an Exchequer grant
rather than by increasing the standard rates of contributions for either
employees or employers, which remain at 9 per cent and 10.4 per cent
respectively, Mr Peter Lilley, secretary of state for social security, said
in a statement yesterday.
He added: 'This legislation will also introduce the 1 per cent additional
rebate for appropriate personal pension holders aged 30 and over.
In line with the Social Security Contributions and Benefits Act 1992, the
lower earnings limit for class 1 contributions is to be raised to Pounds 56
a week, which is the nearest whole pound to the basic retirement pension
rate for a single person from April 1993.
The upper earnings limit is to be raised to Pounds 420 a week, which is
slightly less than seven and a half times the new basic pension rate as
provided by the Social Security Contributions and Benefits Act. These new
earnings limits will replace the current ones of Pounds 54 and Pounds 405.
Under the current structure, employees whose earnings reach the lower
earnings limit will continue to pay an initial contribution of 2 per cent of
that limit, and standard rate contributions of 9 per cent on that portion of
their earnings which exceeds the lower but not the upper earnings limit.
'For employers, the reduced contribution rates of 4.6 per cent, 6.6 per cent
and 8.6 per cent for the lower paid will continue. However, the thresholds
for these rates will be raised so that from April 1993 they apply to weekly
earnings which fall below the ceilings of Pounds 95, Pounds 140, and Pounds
195 respectively, compared with Pounds 90, Pounds 135 and Pounds 190 at
present.
Neither the employee nor his employer will have to pay any contributions if
earnings are less than Pounds 56 a week. Those whose earnings do not exceed
Pounds 405 (the former upper earnings limit) will pay 14 pence a week less
in contributions than at present. This is because a further Pounds 2 of
their weekly earnings will be subject to a deduction of 2 per cent rather
than 9 per cent.
For employees with earnings above Pounds 405 a week, the maximum possible
increase will be Pounds 1.21 a week. Employers' contributions will generally
be unchanged, although some will pay less where employees' earnings which
were above the former thresholds fall below the new thresholds.
There will be no increase for employers of the higher paid since there is no
upper earnings limit for employers' contributions.
The statutory review of the contracted-out rebate for employees and
employers, the result of which was announced last February, resulted in a
reduction in the rebate from April 1993. Although the main rates of
contributions remain unchanged, the effect of the reduced rebate is that
many employees will pay a little more.
Those with earnings between Pounds 110 and Pounds 405 (the former upper
earnings limit) will pay up to 59 pence a week more. Those who earn more
than Pounds 405 will pay contributions on the next Pounds 15 of earnings
from next April (ie up to Pounds 420 a week, the proposed upper earnings
limit), a maximum increase of Pounds 1.67 a week. Contracted-out employees
who earn Pounds 110 or less will pay the same or slightly less.
Because of the fall in the rebate, employers will generally pay more,
although some will pay less where employees' earnings which were above the
former thresholds fall below the new thresholds.
The flat-rate class 2 contribution will be raised by 20 pence to Pounds 5.55
a week. There will be no increase in the rate of class 4 contributions,
currently 6.3 per cent. The annual limits of profits between which class 4
contributions are paid will be raised to Pounds 6,340 and Pounds 21,840 from
Pounds 6,120 and Pounds 21,060 respectively. Self-employed people who pay
only class 2 contributions will pay an extra Pounds 10.40 a year in 1993/94.
For people with profits between Pounds 6,340 and Pounds 21,060 (the former
upper profits limit) class 4 contributions will be reduced by Pounds 13.86
per year assuming an unaltered level of profits. For those self-employed
people with profits at or above the new upper profits limit, the annual
charge for class 4 contributions will be Pounds 35.28 higher.
The rate of class 3 (Voluntary) contributions will be raised by 20 pence to
Pounds 5.45 a week.
The allocation to the National Health Service, currently 1.05 per cent from
employees and 0.9 per cent from employers, remains unchanged.
As usual I shall be laying a draft order before parliament together with a
report by the government actuary describing the effects of my proposals
(which) will take effect from 6 April 1993.'
Mr Lilley said that benefit rates would be raised by 3.6 per cent next
April, in line with the Retail Prices Index in the year to September 1992.
He added that planned expenditure on social security would rise to Pounds
79.8bn in 1993/94. It would go up to Pounds 82.9bn in 1994/95 and Pounds
87bn in 1995/96.
</TEXT>
