<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Details: Incentives for investment in
equipment - Inland Revenue
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT yes-terday acted to increase business confidence by
encouraging companies to bring forward new investment in equipment and
buildings.
The proposals involve a new 40 per cent first year allowance for expenditure
on machinery and plant (excluding cars and certain other assets) incurred by
businesses in the 12 months ending October 31 next year.
The Inland Revenue, in a statement yesterday, said: 'This will be given in
place of the writing down allowance of 25 per cent currently available in
the year the expenditure is incurred. The balance of expenditure will
continue to be written down for tax purposes in subsequent years at 25 per
cent per annum on a reducing balance basis.
The proposed increase in first-year relief for machinery and plant will mean
that over half the cost of equipment incurred between now and October 31,
1993 can be written off against tax within the first couple of years of its
life. Similarly, about a quarter of the cost of new buildings qualifying for
initial allowances can be written off over the same period.
The cost of these new reliefs will be about Pounds 200m in 1993-94 and
Pounds 500m in 1994-95. Subsequently, tax yields will be rather higher than
they would otherwise be because reliefs on the balance of expenditure will
be less.
The legislation for these measures will be included in the 1993 Finance
Bill. The intention is to publish draft clauses before the end of the year.
The new 40 per cent first year allowance will be available for expenditure
which is incurred on machinery and plant (excluding cars and certain other
assets described in paragraph 8. below) between November 1, 1992 and October
31, 1993.
At present, most expenditure on machinery and plant qualifies for writing
down allowances at the rate of 25 per cent per annum on a reducing balance
basis (that is to say, relief of 25 per cent of the full cost is given in
the year that the equipment is bought; 25 per cent of the remaining balance
is given in the second year; and so on for subsequent years).
The rules for the new first year allowance will work like those which
operated when similar allowances were generally available in the past.
Relief will accordingly be given in place of the writing down allowance that
is normally available in the year in which the expenditure is incurred, with
the balance of expenditure written down in future years at the same rate as
now. Qualifying expenditure will therefore be given relief at the rate of 40
per cent in the first year, to be followed by 25 per cent of the remaining
balance in the second year, 25 per cent of the balance in the third year,
and so on for subsequent years.
Businesses will be able to disclaim all or any part of the first year
allowance, should they wish to do so.
For this purpose, the existing definition of 'incurred' in Section 159
Capital Allowances Act (CAA) 1990 will apply. This means that expenditure
will generally be regarded as incurred on the date when the obligation to
pay for the asset becomes unconditional. The main exception to this rule is
where the period of credit allowed is longer than four months.
In these cases, the date on which the bill for the asset is payable is
regarded as the date on which the expenditure is incurred.
In addition, the rule for pre-trading expenditure in section 83(2) CAA 1990
(which deems such expenditure to be incurred on the first day of trading)
will not apply for the purpose of determining whether the expenditure falls
within the year ending October 31, 1993. In other words, first year
allowances will only be due where the expenditure concerned is actually
incurred in that year.
The new 40 per cent first year allowance will apply to all expenditure on
machinery and plant currently qualifying for 25 per cent writing down
allowances except:
Cars, other than taxis, short term hire cars and mobility allowance vehicles
for the disabled (as defined in Section 36 CAA 1990)
Most assets which are acquired from a connected person; or are sold and
leased back; or are acquired in a transaction the sole or main benefit of
which is to obtain a first year allowance (ie. expenditure within the scope
of Sections 75 and 76 CAA 1990).
Where machinery or plant depreciates rapidly, taxpayers will be able to
elect for short life treatment in the usual way.
This means that a full deduction against profits can be taken for any
unrelieved depreciation when the asset is sold or scrapped.
The new 20 per cent initial allowance will be available for industrial and
agricultural buildings which:
Currently qualify for writing down allowances. Are constructed under a
contract entered into between 1 November 1992 and 31 October 1993.
And are brought into use for the purposes of a qualifying trade by December
31, 1994.
Expenditure on structures within the definition of industrial and
agricultural buildings is currently written off over a period of 25 years,
normally at the rate of 4 per cent of the original cost each year, starting
from the year in which the building is brought into use.
The rules for the new relief will work like those which operated when
similar allowances were generally available for qualifying buildings in the
past.
So, relief for 20 per cent of the cost of the building will be available in
the tax year in which the expenditure is incurred, subject to the building
being brought into use by December 31, 1994.
Allowances which are given, based on an intention to bring the building into
use by this date, will be withdrawn where this condition is not, in the
event, met.
The balance of relief will continue to be given at the rate of 4 per cent of
the original cost of the building per annum from the tax year in which it is
brought into use (ie the balance of expenditure, after taking the 20 per
cent initial allowance, will be written off over the next 20 years).
In cases where the expenditure is incurred in the same year in which the
building is brought into use, both an initial allowance and a writing down
allowance will be available, ie. the total allowance due in that year will
be 24 per cent.
Businesses will be able to disclaim all or any part of the initial allowance
should they wish to do so.
Expenditure will qualify for the new 20 per cent initial allowance if it is
incurred under:
A legally binding contract made in the year ended 31 October 1993.
And the claimant was contractually committed to the expenditure by that
contract.
Expenditure which a person incurs by exercising an option in a contract is
not expenditure incurred under that contract. It is expenditure incurred
under a new contract made when the option is exercised.
Such expenditure will qualify for the initial allowance where the new
contract meets the conditions that are set out above.
An industrial building or structure will qualify for initial allowances if
it is brought into use for one of the trades qualifying for the purposes of
writing down allowances, as set out in section 18(1) CAA 1990. The list
includes:
Factories and other premises used for manufacturing.
Buildings or structures in use for the purposes of transport, dock, inland
navigation, water, sewerage, electricity or hydraulic power undertakings.
Tunnel, bridge or toll road undertakings.
Certain storage trades.
Mine, oil well or other mineral workings.
Cultivating land (except where the separate agricultural buildings allowance
is available).
Catching fish or shellfish.
Hotels which qualify for writing down allowances under the industrial
buildings rules will also qualify for an initial allowance.
The definition of a qualifying hotel is in section 19 CAA 1990. In summary,
the hotel must be a permanent structure which meets all the following
conditions:
It must be open for at least four months in the season.
When open it must have at least 10 bedrooms available for letting.
The sleeping accommodation offered must consist wholly or mainly of bedrooms
available for letting.
Meals, bed making and room cleaning services must normally be provided.
Initial allowances will also be available for expenditure on buildings
currently qualifying for agricultural buildings allowances.
This relieves expenditure incurred for the purposes of husbandry on the
construction of farmhouses, farm buildings, cottages, fences and other
works, such as ditches and drains (section 123 CAA 1990).
The allowances are restricted for any private use by the farmer; for
example, in the case of a farmhouse.'
EXAMPLE 1
A company which makes up its accounts annually to December 31 makes a
contract on October 1, 1993 to buy a computer for Pounds 15,000.
The computer is to be delivered on October 15, 1993.
Under the contract, the obligation to pay becomes unconditional on October
15, 1993 but actual payment does not have to be made until 30 days later, on
November 15, 1993.
In this case, the expenditure is incurred on October 15, 1993, ie. before
the cut-off date of October 31.
That means the company is entitled to a 40 per cent first-year allowance for
its accounting period ending on December 31, 1993.
The allowance (ie. 40 per cent of Pounds 15,000), to be deducted from the
company's taxable profits, is Pounds 6,000.
If the computer continues to be used during the following year, the company
will be able to claim a 25 per cent writing down allowance against profits
for its accounting period ending on December 31, 1994.
The allowance will be Pounds 2,250, ie. 25 per cent of the unrelieved
expenditure of Pounds 9,000.
Suppose, however, that the computer is sold for Pounds 5,000 in the
company's second year.
In that case, if the company makes a short-life election, it can claim a
deduction against profits for a balancing allowance equal to the unrelieved
depreciation.
The computer cost Pounds 15,000 and the first year allowance in Year 1 was
Pounds 6,000; hence the balancing allowance in Year 2 will be Pounds 4,000
(which is the unrelieved expenditure of Pounds 9,000 less the sale proceeds
of Pounds 5,000).
EXAMPLE 2
A manufacturing company, which has a December 31 accounting date, enters
into a binding contract to build a factory for its trade on July 1, 1993.
The factory is completed in January 1994. The company moves in immediately
and begins production in May 1994.
The 20 per cent initial allowance will be due because:
the contract was made between 1 November 1992 and October 31, 1993;
the building began to be used before December 31, 1994.
If, for instance, the obligation to pay for the factory became unconditional
in January 1994, when the factory was completed, the result will be:
a 20 per cent initial allowance will be due for the year ended December 31,
1994 (this is the year in which the expenditure was incurred under the rules
in section 159 CAA 1990);
a writing down allowance of 4 per cent of the cost will also be due for the
year ended December 31, 1994 because the asset was in use by the end of that
year.
When a building is in use for the purposes of a trade is a question of fact
in each case.
Normally, the test will be met when the building is being used for the
purpose for which it was built.
A building is not in use for the purposes of the trade when it is being
fitted out.
</TEXT>
