<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Details: Public spending targeted for
a tougher bridle - The Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Treasury yesterday stressed that its main target was to limit rises in
public expenditure in its allocations to the departments.
Its statement said: 'Firm control over public expenditure and a sustainable
fiscal position are fundamental to the longer term prospects for the
economy. The government's objective is to reduce public spending as a share
of national income over time. Because of the effects of the cycle, the ratio
of public spending to national income is expected to rise slightly in
1993-94, to a level still well below the peaks seen following previous
recessions. Thereafter it will resume its downward trend.
The achievement of the government's medium-term public expenditure objective
will be supported by the new system of public expenditure control announced
in July. Under the new system, expenditure will be measured against a new
spending aggregate - the new control total (NCT). The NCT includes local
authority self-financed expenditure but excludes the main elements of
cyclical social security, privatisation proceeds and debt interest. Growth
in the NCT will be constrained to a rate which ensures that total public
spending - general government expenditure - grows by less than the economy
as a whole over the economic cycle.
The new arrangements involve a top-down approach to public expenditure
planning, focusing first on what can be afforded and then on how the
available resources should best be allocated to meet the government's
priorities.
The new expenditure plans meet the remit for the public expenditure survey
set by the cabinet in July - maintaining existing cash plans for 1993-94 and
restricting growth in the new control total thereafter to give average real
growth over the three years no higher than 1 1/2 per cent.
The new plans imply a planning total for 1993-94 of Pounds 244.5bn, the
figure set in last year's Autumn Statement.
Consistent with this, the new control total has been set at Pounds 243.8bn
for 1993-94, and at Pounds 253.6bn for 1994-95 and Pounds 263.3bn for
1995-96.
The real growth in the new control total implied by these figures is 2.3 per
cent in 1993-94, 0.7 per cent in 1994-95 and 1 per cent in 1995-96. Over the
three year period, the new control total is planned to grow on average by
1.4 per cent in real terms. The corresponding figure for the previous three
years was 3.2 per cent.
The new control totals include reserves of Pounds 4bn in 1993-94, Pounds 7bn
in 1994-95 and Pounds 10bn in 1995-96.
These are a little lower than the corresponding figures last year,
reflecting the changed nature of the control system.
The chancellor announced a series of measures to provide a substantial boost
to capital spending by both public and private sectors.
There will be a time-limited increase in the capital allowances available in
the first year for investment in plant and machinery (excluding cars); and a
special initial allowance for industrial and agricultural buildings.
There will be important changes in the use of private finance to enable the
public and private sectors to work more effectively together, particularly
on infrastructure projects.
The temporary relaxation of the local authority capital receipts rules
announced yesterday will be worth over Pounds 1bn over the survey period.
Restraint on current spending has also helped make room for protecting
capital.
The new plans include:
Maintenance of the national roads programme at the level previously planned.
Because of the fall in construction prices the level of new starts in
1993-94 will be nearly double the level likely to be achieved this year.
Total investment by British Rail and London Transport in 1993-94 expected in
real terms to be almost double the level in 1979.
The leasing of some Pounds 150m new rolling stock by BR in the next three
years, provided suitable leases are offered
Provision for the Jubilee Line extension.
Health capital spending in England at a record level next year of nearly
Pounds 2.1bn.
Privatisation proceeds, which are not part of the new control total and do
not therefore affect expenditure, are projected at Pounds 5.5bn in both
1993-94 and 1994-95, in line with previous plans, and at Pounds 1bn in
1995-96.
The planning total for the current year is forecast at Pounds 226.1bn, in
line with the plans in last year's Autumn Statement after allowing for
classification changes and the Pounds 750m housing recovery package.
The overall objective for public expenditure is expressed in terms of the
wider aggregate, general government expenditure (GGE), excluding
privatisation proceeds. GGE includes all of social security expenditure and
central government debt interest.
Total government spending as measured by GGE as a share of national income
is likely to rise to an estimated 44 per cent in 1992-93, mainly as a result
of the recession. It is projected to rise a little further to 45 1/2 per
cent in 1993-94. The government is determined to reduce this ratio, although
it is below the recession-related peaks of 49 1/4 per cent in 1975-76 and 47
1/2 per cent in 1982-83.
It is expected to fall to 45 per cent in 1994-95 and 44 1/4 per cent in
1995-96.
The survey has been an extremely tough one, requiring difficult decisions of
all cabinet ministers.
No programme has been protected from intense scrutiny for savings. But,
where possible, the government has sought to give priority to capital
spending and to other expenditure that contributes to the long-term health
of the economy.
Pay: settlements in the public sector in the coming year will be restricted
to a maximum of 1 1/2 per cent in order to keep pay bills as low as
possible. Without pay restraint there would be less room for spending by
government departments, the NHS and local authorities on services to the
public and on capital.
Transport: the cash plans agreed for the national road programme last year
have been maintained, permitting increased activity as a result of lower
construction prices. The plans provide for higher real investment by BR in
1993-94 than at any time in the 1980s.
They also include provision of over Pounds 1.2bn over the next three years
for the Jubilee Line extension, which will go ahead subject to satisfactory
completion of legal agreements. The government is seeking to encourage
greater levels of transport investment in the medium term through the new
initiatives on private finance.
To encourage the development of a private-sector leasing market for rolling
stock in the lead up to privatisation, BR will be allowed to lease some
Pounds 150m of new rolling stock over the next three financial years.
Housing: the government made a manifesto commitment to provide 153,000 homes
over three years through the Housing Corporation. The new plans should
enable this figure to be comfortably achieved. The government will be
looking for a growing private-sector contribution to the corporation's
programme.
Education: central government spending on education, including support for
local authorities, will be Pounds 9.5bn in 1993-94, Pounds 0.5bn or 3 per
cent higher in real terms than the equivalent forecast out-turn in 1992-93.
The plans will fund an increase of 8 per cent in students attending further
education and sixth form colleges next year, and a 25 per cent increase over
three years, as well as the expansion of grant maintained schools outlined
in the White Paper Choice and Diversity. Provision has also been made to
enable participation in higher education to remain constant at record
levels, following the rapid rise in numbers in recent years.
Employment: the new plans provide real growth of 1 per cent in 1993-94 over
the planned level in 1992-93, which will allow for 500,000 more
opportunities to the unemployed, Youth Training places for a higher
proportion of school leavers and the creation of a new adult training and
work preparation programme.
In addition Training and Enterprise Councils (Tecs) will have more
flexibility to decide how best to use their resources in line with local
labour market needs; and extra money has been provided for schemes such as
Investors in People which are based on close collaboration between Tecs and
local business communities.
Health: planned spending on the National Health Service in England in
1993-94 will be Pounds 29bn, Pounds 1.6bn higher than the plans for 1992-93.
This represents a real-terms increase of 1 per cent over forecast out-turn,
and should allow for growth in hospital activity of at least 2 1/2 per cent.
Capital spending by health authorities and NHS trusts is likely to be at a
record level of almost Pounds 2.1bn.
Defence: during the period covered by the new plans the benefits of the
Options for Change review will be secured and some further savings will be
made consistent with the policies underlying it. Defence spending will fall
by 3 per cent in real terms next year, partly reflecting the much lower pay
settlements now expected, and will continue to decline in real terms in the
following two years.
In total, expenditure on defence is planned to fall in real terms by 10 1/2
per cent between 1992-93 and 1995-96. Over the same period, defence
expenditure will fall as a percentage of GDP from 4 per cent to 3 1/4 per
cent.
Social security: Pounds 3bn has been added to plans for social security
spending in 1993-94, honouring existing commitments. The plans maintain the
real value of social security benefits, most of which will go up by 3.6 per
cent in April 1993.
The increase also reflects the impact of higher unemployment, and of higher
take-up rates for other benefits. The new plans take account of further
action to combat fraud and recover overpayments.
Local government: central government support for local authority revenue
expenditure will rise by 3.7 per cent in England next year compared with the
current year and total standard spending by 3.1 per cent.
The total revenue to be raised from domestic taxpayers in the first year of
the new council tax will be similar in cash terms to the amount being raised
through the community charge in the current year. There will be a special
grant of Pounds 539m next year in England, including Pounds 140m of new
money, to help local authorities discharge their new responsibilities for
community care.
The secretaries of state for the environment, Scotland and Wales will make
announcements about the details of the local authority settlements later
this month.
Overseas Development: planned UK external assistance will rise by 1995-96 by
more than Pounds 200m in cash terms, or 10 per cent, compared with 1992-93
plans. Aid to developing countries will rise in 1993-94 by nearly 1 per cent
in real terms compared with 1992-93 plans, to about Pounds 1,900m. It will
be maintained at that level for the following two years.
Legal departments: the new plans provide additional resources of around
Pounds 0.4bn for legal aid next year. Total expenditure on legal aid is
forecast to rise to Pounds 1.5bn by 1995-96.
The government will be taking steps to secure improved value for money by
more effective targeting and by payment arrangements which encourage
efficiency and quality.
Agriculture: the new plans provide for substantial increases in provision in
each year, mainly reflecting the reform of the Common Agricultural Programme
agreed by European Community agriculture ministers in May 1992.
The reform is expected to lower the cost of the CAP to consumers by reducing
prices, with compensation to farmers in the form of increased direct
payments.
Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland: The system for allocating to Scotland,
Wales and Northern Ireland the consequential effects of expenditure
decisions in England remains in place.
The formula has been updated to take account of the latest population
figures contained in the 1991 census.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 25
</PAGE>
