<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Analysis: Council tax bills still
hang in balance - Local government
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SIZE of individual council tax bills next year still hangs in the
balance after yesterday's announcement. However, the statement did show,
that the government prefers to exercise its extensive powers to limit local
authority spending rather than to use taxpayers' money in smoothing the
introduction of the property-based council tax.
The assertion from Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, that the
statement means there is no reason why local authorities in England should
have to raise more next year from the council tax than they are raising this
year from the poll tax, depends on assumptions not shared by local councils.
Among those assumptions are the opportunities for further efficiency
savings, and authorities' ability to keep to a maximum increase of 1.5 per
cent on their pay bills. Above all, they do not take account of the
difference between government plans at the start of the year and the
increase which occurs when the local budgets are drawn up and the money is
actually spent.
Local authority associations were swift to warn yesterday that the
government's plans could mean drastic cuts in services and jobs. Mr Jeremy
Beecham, the leader of the Labour-controlled Assocaiton of Metropolitan
Authorities, said: 'The target falls far short of what is needed to provide
crucial services.'
In particular, the associations pointed out that councils are already
committed to Pounds 350m more spending on pay next year as a result of pay
deals agreed with groups such as the police and the fire service. The cost
of 1.5 per cent for the next round of pay deals represents a further Pounds
300m or so.
Year-on-year comparisons in local government finance are never easy, but
this year the task is made harder by the shift in functions and by the
change from the poll tax to the council tax.
The new figure for total standard spending - the government's plans for
local authority budgets - is Pounds 41.142bn. This is, the department of the
environment says, an increase of 3.1 per cent on the plans for this year,
taking account of local government's loss of most responsibilities for
further education, and its gain of responsibility for community care.
Those changes carry in themselves the prospect of further disagreements
between central and local government. The new grant of Pounds 539m for
community care is considered insufficient by the authorities. They also
argue that in deducting about Pounds 2.4bn from the spending total for the
loss of further education the government has overstated the amount that
councils were spending, and has, as a result, left them in an even more
difficult position.
The increase in total local spending is noticeably lower, compared with the
amount that councils are actually spending this year. This is set to
overshoot the government's target by just over Pounds 1bn, taking spending
for this year to Pounds 42.9bn.
Overall, English councils will receive an extra Pounds 1.2bn in money from
central government and the business rate, as aggregate external finance
rises to Pounds 33.519bn.
The three local authority associations, including those dominated by Tories
as well as those led by Labour, said that the target represented an increase
of less than 0.5 per cent over the current year's budget.
In any event, the final spending outcome for next year will be higher than
the government's intention. This is because even the stricter regime of
capping local spending which will be announced later this month leaves some
leeway for spending slightly over the government's plans, and also because
councils will have to take account of poll tax arrears, which remain outside
the process of limiting local spending.
The range of council tax bills across the country will not be apparent until
later this month when Mr Howard announces the grant distribution and the
provisional criteria for capping local spending.
However, one element in the amounts people will have to pay in council tax
will be the scale of the transitional relief scheme, which is included in
the total Pounds 33.519bn of central government support and the business
rate. Latest estimates put the cost of this for next year at about Pounds
500m maximum, with those in lower property bands qualifying more readily for
help.
The increase in the business rate by the inflation rate - 3.5 per cent  - is
a blow for business organisations which have been agitating for a freeze.
It was inevitable that the government would put the rate up by the maximum
possible because a fall in the number of businesses paying has already led
to a shortfall in the national non-domestic rate pool from which the
government distributes the business rate to local councils.
</TEXT>
