<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Analysis: Eligibility rules to be
tightened - Legal aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's plans to curb legal aid expenditure would result in 'a
massive cut in the number of people eligible for legal aid', The Law Society
warned yesterday.
The government plans the net cost of legal aid to rise to Pounds 1.284bn in
1993-94, Pounds 1.406bn in 1994-95 and 1.528bn in 1995-96 - representing
increases of Pounds 399m, Pounds 502m and Pounds 606m respectively over last
year's public expenditure targets.
This will result in an increase, on average, of 10 per cent a year from
present levels. But to ensure that legal aid spending 'did not rise even
faster', the Lord Chancellor said it was necessary to take a number of
measures from April next to tighten eligibility rules.
Lord Mackay's proposals include:
a reduction in the level of disposable income at which an applicant is
entitled to free legal aid to income support levels - a reduction from
Pounds 3,060 per annum to Pounds 2,213 per annum.
dependants' allowances for civil legal aid will be reduced to income support
levels;
equivalent changes will be made to financial eligibility regimes for
criminal legal aid and for advice and assistance under the Green Form
scheme;
the upper eligibility limits for civil legal aid (the level of disposable
income at which people cease to be eligible) will not be increased next
year;
contributions for those above the free legal aid limits will increase from
one-quarter of disposable income to one-third, and will continue for the
life of the case.
The Law Society, the solicitors' governing body, said it was 'devastated' by
the proposals. 'It will result in a massive reduction in access to justice
taking more than 7m people out of eligibility for legal aid,' a spokesman
said.
Mr Paul Boateng, shadow legal affairs spokesman, accused the Lord Chancellor
of caving in under Treasury pressure and of 'betraying his office as
protector of the rights of all people regardless of means to equality under
the law and access to the courts'.
</TEXT>
