FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Analysis: Slight decline in
expenditure - Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND'S share of government expenditure will decline slightly as a result
of updating the formula under which most of the Scottish Office budget is
determined. The change is due to the decline in the Scottish population
compared with that of England.
However, the effect will be marginal in the next financial year and should
be offset by measures worth Pounds 208m, announced by Mr Ian Lang, Scottish
secretary, to boost construction and help business.
The Scottish Office's 1993/94 budget will be Pounds 13.5bn, a rise of 2 per
cent in real terms, taking into account new responsibilities for
universities and community care.
Since 1979 the Scottish Office, which funds such matters as health,
education, law and order and local government in Scotland, has received 11.7
per cent of any increase in England's share of government spending on
similar items. This will fall to 10.6 per cent. The change may satisfy
English MPs who claim that Scotland receives too large a share of spending,
but does not affect the basic expenditure to which annual increases are
added.
Wales and Northern Ireland have benefited slightly from the updating of
regional spending rules. On the 1991 census, they will receive 6.02 per cent
and 2.87 per cent respectively of any changes to comparable programmes in
England.
