<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Analysis: Marginal impact on new
investment - Capital allowances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BY RAISING capital allowances on new investment in plant machinery and
buildings, the chancellor has made new investment marginally more
attractive. But the Treasury's growth forecasts suggest this incentive will
have no more than a marginal effect on investment.
The statement introduces a 40 per cent first-year allowance for expenditure
on machinery and plant incurred by businesses in the 12 months ending
October 31 next year, rather than 25 per cent as at present, and a 20 per
cent allowance on new buildings.
Companies will use the allowances to write off more of the cost of
investment against their corporate tax liability in the year in which the
investment is made. The balance of expenditure will continue to be written
down in subsequent years at 25 per cent a year. The measure will cost Pounds
200m in 1993-94 and Pounds 500m in 1994-95.
But while the Treasury expects total fixed investment to grow by  1/4 per
cent next year, business investment is expected to remain stagnant. The rise
in total investment is accounted for by a projected 1 per cent rise in
private dwellings investment and a 1 3/4 per cent increase in public
investment, neither of which is affected.
The corporate tax change effectively reverses, for a limited period, a
central element of the 1984 change in corporation taxes, piloted through by
the then chancellor Mr Nigel Lawson. The increase in allowances, in effect,
rebalances the taxes that companies pay on new investments by giving greater
relief in the year in which the investment is carried out.
The problem with raising allowances, according to the Institute of Fiscal
Studies, is that it is an expensive way of generating what tends to be a
small amount of activity. Investment which would have occurred anyway
qualifies for the extra relief as well as any new investment the relief
generates. If investment is discouraged by depressed consumer demand,
marginal tax changes tend to make little difference to investment volume.
The Labour party proposed an almost identical change in allowances for new
investment in its election manifesto. The Labour party estimated its
increase in allowances would cost Pounds 600m in the first year, assuming a
larger investment response.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
