<PROFILE>_AN-CKMB5ADKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921113
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Analysis: A long-awaited welcome for
private sector support - Infrastructure projects financing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PLENDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GREATER use of private finance for public sector infrastructure projects
looks, at first glance, to be a notable retreat from a long-held government
position. But in reality it is a logical development in public finance that
reflects the transformation in the composition of the public sector since
the Tories first came to power in 1979.
In his recently published memoirs, former chancellor Lord Lawson reveals
that Sir Leo Pliatzky, a distinguished former Treasury official who
specialised in public finance, was asked in the early 1980s to devise new
means of financing nationalised industries. His proposals for bringing
private sector funding to state enterprise were found lacking in radicalism
by Lawson and Pliatzky's unpublished report was shelved. But his approach is
now back in fashion because the privatisation programme has slowed down. The
state has been left with a recalcitrant rump of enterprises which defy early
privatisation and pose continuing financing problems.
There has, in addition, been some retreat from the traditional Treasury
hostility to such private financing. The so-called Ryrie rules, which
imposed stringent tests for the use of private money in public projects,
were abolished in 1989. Yet the consequent loosening in the criteria for
using private funds led to only a handful of cases in which private sector
money was invested in infrastructure projects.
The Autumn Statement's proposals, though somewhat tentative, are intended to
lower further the hurdles for private sector financiers. Where private firms
are responsible for government-approved projects and are able to recoup the
cost through charges at the point of use, the Whitehall mandarins will not
apply a value-for-money test against a theoretical public sector
alternative. This is important because public sector enterprise enjoys cheap
capital thanks to the government's implicit or explicit guarantee. This
saddled the private sector with a competitive handicap.
The government also appears to have shed some of its ideological antipathy
for joint ventures between the public and private sector provided there is a
'sensible' sharing of risks between the two sides. The intention is for the
government to specify its contribution in terms of money and risk, and then
invite participation through open competition. One ideological remnant,
however, is that the state will eschew controlling stakes. Leasing, hitherto
used in the public sector mainly by local authorities to dodge the financial
constraints imposed by central government, is also to be given wider scope.
The more relaxed approach to joint public-private sector financing will no
doubt be welcomed by the construction and transport sectors and by the
banks. There is a clear opportunity for creative financial engineering. But
how great an opportunity is a moot point. One of the reasons why the
disappearance of the Ryrie rules had so little impact was that few
infrastructure investments hold out much hope of an adequate commercial
return.
By definition, infrastructure projects like the Channel Tunnel or the
Jubilee Line extension are very long term, subject to planning delays and
cost over-runs. Private capital is notoriously shy of such high-risk, long
term investments. Plans for building toll roads, meantime, have to contend
with the fact that the bulk of the existing, competing road network is free.
The ability to bring in large amounts of private capital may be contingent
on the introduction of road pricing or the imaginative use of government
grants.
Perhaps the biggest question mark over the viability of the Autumn
Statement's proposals concerns the location of risk in the partnership. The
government insists that there must be no creative accounting and that the
private sector must genuinely assume risk if the sums borrowed or leased are
not to fall on the public sector borrowing requirement. The banks and
building societies may be able to meet such criteria in financing the
government's new plans for the housing market, since the Pounds 750m of
houses to be nationalised offer security (albeit with initial valuation
problems) and a potential rental stream when let. Elsewhere, there will be
complex problems in defining and evaluating risk.
The one thing additional private financing will not do for the government is
help generate an economic recovery. The impact, if it is more than modest,
is unlikely to be felt before the end of the decade.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
</DOC>
