<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Analysis: Small satisfaction for the
trade sector - Export financing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID DODWELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH exporters seeking positive government support in the Autumn
Statement were left unsated yesterday - pleased to have extra cover
available, but still complaining that the cost of export credit insurance
remains significantly higher for UK exporters than for most international
competitors.
The additional Pounds 700m of export credit guarantee cover is to be spread
over the present financial year and 1993-94. Just Pounds 200m is to be added
to cover this year, with Pounds 500m to be added next year - amounting to
about a quarter of the total exports guaranteed by the Export Credit
Guarantees Department (ECGD).
The extra guarantees are to be focused on 11 markets - all of them countries
in which British exporters are heavily involved. These markets are China,
Hong Kong, South Africa, India, Indonesia, Kuwait, Malaysia, Mexico, Oman,
Turkey and Zimbabwe.
The first five of these are defined by the ECGD as 'concentrated markets' -
meaning that they account for such a large proportion of the ECGD's overall
foreign exposure that new cover is unavailable.
Exporters have frequently argued that this restraint prevents them from
winning orders in some of their biggest markets. So the decision to provide
an extra Pounds 500m on an annualised basis - an increase of about 30 per
cent on cover presently available - will be welcome.
'It's encouraging to see that the government has taken some note of what
industry has been saying,' said Mr Philip Hills, head of export finance at
the Midland Bank: 'In some of these eleven markets there has been growing
concern that the ECGD was unable to cover British exporters' initiatives.'
For example, British Aerospace is negotiating with the Indonesian government
to sell Hawk jets worth several hundred million pounds. Until yesterday's
provision of extra cover, BAe would have been unlikely to have access to
export credit guarantees for the deal.
But the availability of extra cover does nothing to resolve the principal
complaint of British exporters - that the cost of export credit insurance
premiums is so much higher than costs for competitors that they suffer a
significant competitive disadvantage.
All the ECGD said yesterday is that premium rates were reviewed - and in
some cases trimmed - in April this year as part of the annual review
process, and they would not be reviewed again until next spring.
The government may feel that the competitive advantage won by exporters as a
result of the recent devaluation of sterling is sufficient to leave premium
rates untouched.
This analysis may be simplistic, however, since many of the components going
into British exports are imported, and so have become more expensive
following devaluation.
One trade financier said: 'Devaluation may have helped for exports inside
Europe, but has probably made little difference in overseas markets where
the cost of export credit insurance is going to bite. The evidence at
present is clear - we are still uncompetitive with some of our fiercest
competitors because of the cost of insurance.'
Since the ECGD introduced in May 1991 its 'portfolio management system'
(PMS) - designed to link export premium rates more closely to the existing
risks - Britain has become one of the most expensive insurers in the world.
The government has nevertheless been unflinching in its commitment to the
system, arguing that the new premiums provide an accurate assessment of the
risks of non-payment involved in selling goods to developing country
markets. It insists that taxpayers should not subsidise insurance premiums
when exporters face a very real chance of not being paid for their goods.
Some other industrial exporters have recently raised insurance premium
rates, but few by enough to reach British levels. Exporters still complain
of premiums three and four times higher than those for competitors in risky
markets in developing countries.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
