<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Details: Recession brings spending
shift
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SHIFT of spending from weapons purchases to payments for the poor is among
the changes forced on the government by the longer-than-expected recession.
There is also a big switch in the pattern of spending by local authorities,
with the Treasury being willing to sanction a large increase in spending
which councils finance themselves while cracking down on payments to them by
central government.
At the same time, funds channelled to councils by central government have
been shaved back.
Councils' self-financed spending is due to increase to Pounds 11.1bn from
the Pounds 9bn planned a year ago, but at the same time the Treasury will
crack down on payments to them by central government.
The new plans also indicate a cut in transport spending in relation to
existing plans, while health spending has emerged virtually unscathed.
Spending on defence will total Pounds 23.5bn in 1993-94, 4 per cent down on
the Pounds 24.5bn sketched in for the year in the 1991 Autumn Statement,
including the effects of a technical adjustment for pension costs.
Some of the Pounds 1bn taken from defence funds will be injected into a 6
per cent overall rise in social security spending, up sharply from the
Pounds 76.1bn envisaged a year ago to a new estimate of fully Pounds 80.5bn.
Under new Treasury rules outlined yesterday, only that element of social
security spending which is reckoned to be unrelated to the economic cycle
will be counted as part of the new control total introduced by the
government to curb rises in overall spending.
After taking into account various changes in classification, the new control
total - set at Pounds 243.8bn for 1993-94 - is equivalent to the Pounds
244.5bn planning total for this year announced by the Treasury 12 months
ago.
Overall social security spending is divided into two parts: Pounds 65bn
which is unrelated to the economic cycle and Pounds 15.5bn linked to the
economic downturn. That takes the form of unemployment pay and some elements
of income support to people under 65.
The Treasury is assuming that unemployment will average 2.8m this year and
total 2.9m in 1993-94, staying at this figure until 1995-96.
Even as recently as the March Budget, the Treasury was assuming that growth
would be much higher during this period, with unemployment as a result being
limited to 2.5m.
As a consequence of the shift in thinking about unemployment, overall social
security spending is likely to continue to rise steeply.
For next year, the Treasury has found it possible to increase social
security spending by making small cuts in other departments' spending -
among them transport - and by pencilling in a Pounds 1.2bn reduction in
finance to European Community funds compared to last year's plans.
Other extra funds have come from reducing the unallocated reserve - which is
part of the 1993-94 spending plans - from Pounds 8bn a year ago to Pounds
4bn.
Some of the comparisons between the different plans for 1993-94, shown in
the table, have been affected by changes in responsi-bilities of specific
departments; for instance the taking over of the responsibilities of the
Department of Energy by the Department of Trade and Industry.
