<HEADLINE>
FT  13 NOV 92 / The Autumn Statement - Details: Disappointment at training
commitment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR PAT WALLACE, who is in charge of government-funded training programmes at
Birmingham Chamber of Commerce, called it an 'autumn non-statement'. He was
disappointed that Mr Lamont had not mentioned training apart from making a
brief reference to youth training.
He was not the only disappointed training chief. 'I welcome the
determination of the government to invest in the development of human
capital,' said Mr Brendan McGuinness, director of education and training at
the Engineering Employers' Federation in the west Midlands. 'I would have
welcomed a stronger commitment in the actual statement to training,' he
added.
Mr Peter Harrisson, managing director of Linread, the fasteners group, said
training was focused too much on the short term.
'You've got to see it long-term as an investment, and that is where one
would have liked to have seen government putting some money in,' Mr
Harrisson said.
Mr Edward Roberts, chief executive of Heath Springs of Redditch and chairman
of G10, the group which liaises between Training and Enterprise Councils and
the government, said: 'From what we can see at first glance it is a help.'
'They haven't smacked the funding, and they have allowed us more
flexibility,' said Mr Richard Archer, a member of the Birmingham Tec board
and a partner at KPMG Peat Marwick, the accountancy firm.
The greater freedom for TECs to run their own operations and to have three
year funding on some training projects Mr Archer classified as 'basic common
sense'. It would will also help those who provide training. 'Our planning
jumps from year to year. If the TECs get more stability, they can pass it on
to us.' He observed it was less difficult to give people qualifications than
to find them jobs when they had qualifications.
'I think the whole thing sounds very good for the West Midlands,' said Mr
Roberts.
</TEXT>
